{{About||the United Kingdom's withdrawal from the European Union|Brexit|the referendum itself|United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016}}
{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}

{{United Kingdom in the European Union}}

After the [[United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016|UK EU membership referendum]] held on 23 June 2016, in which a majority voted to [[Brexit|leave the European Union]], the United Kingdom experienced political and economic upsets, with spillover effects across the rest of the [[European Union]] and the wider world. Prime Minister [[David Cameron]], who had campaigned for Remain, announced his resignation on 24 June, triggering a [[Conservative Party (UK) leadership election, 2016|Conservative leadership election]], won by Home Secretary [[Theresa May]]. Following [[Leader of the Opposition (UK)|Leader of the Opposition]] [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s loss of a [[motion of no confidence]] among the [[Parliamentary Labour Party]], he also faced a [[Labour Party (UK) leadership election, 2016|leadership challenge]], which he won. [[Nigel Farage]] stepped down from leadership of the pro-Leave party [[UKIP]] in July. After the elected party leader resigned, Farage then became the party's interim leader on 5 October until [[Paul Nuttall]] was [[UK Independence Party leadership election, November 2016|elected leader]] on 28 November.

Voting patterns in the referendum varied between areas: [[Gibraltar]], [[Greater London]], many other cities, [[Scotland]] and [[Northern Ireland]] had majorities for Remain; the remainder of England and Wales and most [[Unionism in Ireland|unionist parts of Northern Ireland]] showed Leave majorities.<ref name="Split">{{citation|url=https://www.economist.com/news/britain/21701257-results-paint-picture-angry-country-divided-class-age-and-region-country-divided/|title=The Brexit vote reveals a country split down the middle |newspaper=[[The Economist]] |date=24 June 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref> This fuelled concern among [[Scottish nationalism|Scottish]] and [[Irish nationalism|Irish]] nationalists: the [[First Minister of Scotland]] threatened to withhold legislative consent for any withdrawal legislation and has now formally requested permission to hold a [[Proposed second Scottish independence referendum|second Scottish independence referendum]], while the [[deputy First Minister of Northern Ireland]] called for a referendum on a [[united Ireland]]. The [[Disputed status of Gibraltar|status of Gibraltar]] and that [[London independence|of London]] were also questioned.

In late July 2016, the [[Foreign Affairs Select Committee]] was told that Cameron had refused to allow the [[Civil Service (United Kingdom)|Civil Service]] to make plans for Brexit, a decision the committee described as "an act of gross negligence".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/20/david-cameron-accused-gross-negligence-brexit-contingency-plans|title=Cameron accused of 'gross negligence' over Brexit contingency plans|work=The Guardian|first=Patrick |last=Wintour|date=20 July 2016|accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref>

==Economic effects==
{{main|Economic effects of Brexit}}

Economic arguments were a major element of the referendum debate.  Remainers, including the UK treasury, argued trade would be worse off outside the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hm-treasury-analysis-the-long-term-economic-impact-of-eu-membership-and-the-alternatives|title=HM Treasury analysis: the long-term economic impact of EU membership and the alternatives |publisher=Government of the United Kingdom|access-date=8 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Brexit and the UK's Public Finances|journal=Institute for Fiscal Studies|date=May 2016|issue=IFS Report 116|url=http://www.ifs.org.uk/uploads/publications/comms/r116.pdf|accessdate=18 June 2016}}</ref>  Supporters of withdrawal argued that the cessation of net contributions to the EU would allow for some cuts to taxes or increases in government spending.<ref name=JR14042016TGEABLEU>[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/apr/14/british-austerity-brexit-budget-nhs-disability-benefits-property The end of British austerity starts with Brexit] J. Redwood, ''The Guardian'', 14 April 2016</ref>

On the day after the referendum, [[Bank of England]] Governor [[Mark Carney]] held a press conference to reassure the markets,<ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jun/23/eu-referendum-result-live-counting-leave-remain-brain-in-europe|title=Brexit: Nicola Sturgeon says second Scottish referendum 'highly likely'|first1=Andrew|last1=Sparrow|first2=Matthew|last2=Weaver|first3=Philip|last3=Oltermann|first4=Adam|last4=Vaughan|first5=Anushka|last5=Asthana|first6=Mark|last6=Tran|first7=Jessica|last7=Elgot|first8=Holly|last8=Watt|first9=Jennifer|last9=Rankin|first10=Henry|last10=McDonald|first11=Maev|last11=Kennedy|first12=Frances|last12=Perraudin|first13=Arthur|last13=Neslen|first14=Lisa|last14=O'Carroll|first15=Nadia|last15=Khomami|first16=Steven|last16=Morris|first17=Pamela|last17=Duncan|first18=Katie|last18=Allen|first19=Severin|last19=Carrell|first20=Rowena|last20=Mason|first21=Helena|last21=Bengtsson|first22=Caelainn|last22=Barr|first23=Simon|last23=Goodley|first24=Libby|last24=Brooks|first25=Graeme|last25=Wearden|first26=Ben|last26=Quinn|first27=Randeep|last27=Ramesh|first28=Nick|last28=Fletcher|first29=Jill|last29=Treanor|first30=Justin|last30=McCurry|first31=Richard|last31=Adams|first32=Josh|last32=Halliday|first33=David|last33=Pegg|first34=Claire|last34=Phipps|first35=Deborah|last35=Mattinson|first36=Peter|last36=Walker|date=24 June 2016}}</ref> and two weeks later released £150&nbsp;billion in lending.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jul/05/bank-of-england-releases-150bn-pounds-risks-financial-stability|title=Bank of England releases £150bn of lending and warns on financial stability |author=Jill Trainor|date=5 July 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> Nonetheless, share prices of the five largest British banks fell an average of 21% on the morning after the referendum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-banks-idUSKCN0Z92G8|title=Britain's financial sector reels after Brexit bombshell|date=24 June 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref> All of the [[Big Three (credit rating agencies)|Big Three]] [[credit rating agency|credit rating agencies]] reacted negatively to the vote in June 2016: [[Standard & Poor's]] cut the UK credit rating from AAA to AA, [[Fitch Group]] cut from AA+ to AA, and [[Moody's]] cut the UK's outlook to "negative".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-36644934|title=Ratings agencies downgrade UK credit rating after Brexit vote|publisher=BBC News|date=27 June 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>

When the [[London Stock Exchange]] opened on Friday 24 June, the [[FTSE 100 Index|FTSE 100]] fell from 6338.10 to 5806.13 in the first ten minutes of trading. Near the close of trading on 27 June, the domestically-focused [[FTSE 250 Index]] was down approximately 14% compared to the day before the referendum results were published.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/buttonwood/2016/06/markets-after-referendum |title=Markets after the referendum – Britain faces Project Reality |last=Buttonwood |date=27 June 2016 |website=The Economist |publisher=The Economist Newspaper Limited |access-date=27 June 2016}}</ref> However, by 1 July the FTSE 100 had risen above pre-referendum levels, to a ten-month high representing the index's largest single-week rise since 2011.<ref>{{cite news |date=1 July 2016 |title=Post-Brexit rebound sees FTSE setting biggest weekly rise since 2011 |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/post-brexit-vote-rebound-sees-071820694.html/ |agency=Reuters|location=London, UK |access-date=3 July 2016}}</ref> On 11 July, it officially entered [[bull market]] territory, having risen by more than 20% from its February low.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-36762631|title=FTSE 100 rises to 11-month high|date=11 July 2016}}</ref> The FTSE 250 moved above its pre-referendum level on 27 July.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/07/27/ftse-100-set-to-open-higher-as-markets-eye-us-fed-rates-decision/|title=FTSE 100 hits one-year high and FTSE 250 erases post-Brexit losses as UK economy grows by 0.6pc|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=27 July 2016|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> In the US, the [[S&P 500 Index|S&P 500]], a broader market than the Dow Jones, reached an all-time high on 11 July.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://next.ft.com/content/771c7bba-3cae-3cce-9591-9135675b4d6c|title=S&P 500 hits record high for first time since '15|newspaper=Financial Times|date=11 July 2016|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref>

On the morning of 24 June, the pound sterling fell to its lowest level against the US dollar since 1985.<ref name="bbc.co.uk">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-36570120|title=Brexit after EU referendum: UK to leave EU and David Cameron quits}}</ref> The drop over the day was 8% – the biggest one-day fall in the pound since the introduction of floating exchange rates following the collapse of the [[Bretton Woods system]] in 1971.<ref>{{cite news |last= McGeever |first= Jamie |date= 7 July 2016|title= Sterling's post-Brexit fall is biggest loss in a hard currency|url= https://uk.reuters.com/article/us-britain-markets-sterling/sterlings-post-brexit-fall-is-biggest-loss-in-a-hard-currency-idUKKCN0ZN1R0 |work= |location= |access-date=9 October 2017}}</ref> The pound remained low, and on 8 July became the worst performing major currency of the year,<ref>{{cite news|first=Marianna|last=Duarte De Aragao |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-08/pound-overtakes-argentine-peso-to-become-2016-s-worst-performer |title=Pound Overtakes Argentine Peso to Become 2016's Worst Performer |work=Bloomberg News |publisher=Bloomberg |date=8 July 2016 |accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> although the pound's trade-weighted index is only back at levels seen in the period 2008–2013.<ref>{{cite news|first=Hazel |last=Sheffield |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/pound-sterling-argentine-peso-worst-performing-currency-eu-referendum-brexit-a7127246.html |title=Pound sterling beats Argentine peso to become 2016's worst performing currency |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=8 July 2016 |accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/uk/350200-brexit-peso-pound-worst/ |title=Post-Brexit pound now worst-performing major currency… falling behind Argentine peso |work=RT UK |publisher=RT |date=8 July 2016 |accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Alistair |last=Osborne |url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/own-goal-is-gift-to-argentina-6r70clsw7 |title=Own goal is gift to Argentina |newspaper=The Times |publisher=Times Group Newspapers |date=9 July 2016 |accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>  It was expected that the weaker pound would also benefit aerospace and defence firms, pharmaceutical companies, and professional services companies; the share prices of these companies were boosted after the EU referendum.<ref>[http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/brexit-fallout-rolls-royce-glaxosmithkline-experian-are-big-winners-weak-pound-1569154 Brexit: Here are the three major winners from a weak pound right now] E. Shing, International Business Times, 6 July 2016</ref>

After the referendum the [[Institute for Fiscal Studies]]  published a report funded by the [[Economic and Social Research Council]] which warned that Britain would lose up to £70 billion in reduced economic growth if it didn't retain [[Single Market]] membership with new trade deals unable to make up the difference.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/08/10/britain-could-be-up-to-70billion-worse-off-if-it-leaves-the-sing/|title=Britain could be up to £70billion worse off if it leaves the Single Market after Brexit, IFS warns|author=Steven Swinford|date=10 August 2016|accessdate=11 August 2016}}</ref>  One of these areas is financial services, which are helped by EU-wide "passporting" for financial products, which the [[Financial Times]] estimates indirectly accounts for up to 71,000 jobs and 10 billion pounds of tax annually<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.https://www.ft.com/content/f60b2d44-8a51-11e6-8aa5-f79f5696c731 |title=Claim 'hard Brexit' could cost UK£10bn in tax |newspaper=Financial Times |date=4 October 2016 |accessdate=4 October 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130819141428/http://https/ |archivedate=19 August 2013  }}</ref> and there are concerns that banks may relocate outside the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-37743700 |title=Banks poised to relocate out of UK over Brexit, BBA warns |publisher=BBC News |date=23 October 2016 |accessdate=24 February 2017}}</ref>

On 5 January 2017, [[Andy Haldane]], the Chief Economist and the Executive Director of Monetary Analysis and Statistics at the [[Bank of England]], admitted that forecasts predicting an economic downturn due to the referendum were inaccurate and noted strong market performance after the referendum,<ref>{{cite web | title=Bank of England Economist: Brexit Predictions Were Wrong | url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2017/01/06/bank-england-economist-brexit-predictions-were-wrong.html | date=6 January 2017 | publisher=[[Fox News]] (from the [[Associated Press]]) | accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Inman | first1=Phillip | title=Chief Economist of Bank of England Admits Errors in Brexit Forecasting | url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2017/jan/05/chief-economist-of-bank-of-england-admits-errors | date=5 January 2017 | work=[[The Guardian]] | accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Swinford | first1=Steven | title=Bank of England Admits 'Michael Fish' Moment with Dire Brexit Predictions | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/01/05/bank-england-admits-michael-fish-moment-dire-brexit-predictions/ | date=6 January 2017 | work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] | accessdate=18 January 2017}}</ref>  although some have pointed to prices rising faster than wages.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/mar/24/brexit-vote-experts-data-bank-of-england 'The Brexit vote is starting to have major negative consequences' – experts debate the data] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>

===Economy and business===
{{See also|Brexit and arrangements for science and technology}}
On 27 June, Chancellor of the Exchequer [[George Osborne]] attempted to reassure financial markets that the UK economy was not in serious trouble. This came after media reports that a survey by the [[Institute of Directors]] suggested that two-thirds of businesses believed that the outcome of the referendum would produce negative results as well as falls in the value of sterling and the FTSE 100. Some British businesses had also predicted that investment cuts, hiring freezes and redundancies would be necessary to cope with the results of the referendum.<ref>{{cite news |last=Wood |first=Zoe |date=26 June 2016 |title=Firms plan to quit UK as City braces for more post-Brexit losses |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jun/26/city-of-london-expecting-further-post-brexit-losses-when-trade-reopens |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London, UK |access-date=27 June 2016}}</ref> Osborne indicated that Britain was facing the future "from a position of strength" and there was no current need for an emergency Budget.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/business-36637732 |title=Osborne: UK economy in a position of strength |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=27 June 2016 |website=BBC News – Business |publisher=BBC |access-date=27 June 2016 |quote=George Osborne has said the UK is ready to face the future "from a position of strength" and indicated there will be no immediate emergency Budget.}}</ref> "No-one should doubt our resolve to maintain the fiscal stability we have delivered for this country ... And to companies, large and small, I would say this: the British economy is fundamentally strong, highly competitive and we are open for business."<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/27/europe/uk-brexit-jeremy-corbyn-boris-johnson/ |title=Brexit: UK government shifts to damage control |last1=Dewan |first1=Angela |last2=McKirdy |first2=Euan |date=27 June 2016 |publisher=CNN |access-date=27 June 2016 |quote=Not since World War II has Britain faced such an uncertain future.}}</ref>

On 14 July [[Philip Hammond]], Osborne's successor as Chancellor, told [[BBC News]] the referendum result had caused uncertainty for businesses, and that it was important to send "signals of reassurance" to encourage investment and spending. He also confirmed there would not be an emergency budget: "We will want to work closely with the governor of the Bank of England and others through the summer to prepare for the Autumn Statement, when we will signal and set out the plans for the economy going forward in what are very different circumstances that we now face, and then those plans will be implemented in the Budget in the spring in the usual way."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-36792202 |title=Philip Hammond: Financial markets 'rattled' by Leave vote |publisher=BBC News  |date=14 July 2016 |accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref>

On 12 July, the global investment management company [[BlackRock]] predicted the UK would experience a recession in late 2016 or early 2017 as a result of the vote to leave the EU, and that economic growth would slow down for at least five years because of a reduction in investment.<ref>{{cite news|first=Hazel |last=Sheffield |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/brexit-will-plunge-the-uk-into-a-recession-in-the-next-year-blackrock-says-a7134616.html |title=Brexit will plunge the UK into a recession in the next year, BlackRock says |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=14 July 2016 |accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref> On 18 July, the UK-based economic forecasting group [[ITEM club|EY ITEM club]] suggested the country would experience a "short shallow recession" as the economy suffered "severe confidence effects on spending and business"; it also cut its economic growth forecasts for the UK from 2.6% to 0.4% in 2017, and 2.4% to 1.4% for 2018. The group's chief economic adviser, Peter Soencer, also argued there would be more long-term implications, and that the UK "may have to adjust to a permanent reduction in the size of the economy, compared to the trend that seemed possible prior to the vote".<ref>{{cite news|first=Zlata |last=Rodionova |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/uk-faces-short-recession-as-brexit-uncertainty-hits-house-prices-consumer-spending-and-jobs-ey-a7142616.html |title=UK faces short recession as Brexit uncertainty hits house prices, consumer spending and jobs, EY predicts |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=18 July 2016 |accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref> Senior City investor Richard Buxton  also argued there would be a "mild recession".<ref>{{cite news|first=Robin |last=De Peyer |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/brexit-britain-set-for-recession-as-top-city-figure-warns-leaving-eu-will-be-horrible-a3297781.html |title=Britain 'set for recession' as Richard Buxton calls leaving EU 'horrible' |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=18 July 2016 |accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref> On 19 July, the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF) reduced its 2017 economic growth forecast for the UK from 2.2% to 1.3%, but still expected Britain to be the second fastest growing economy in the G7 during 2016; the IMF also reduced its forecasts for world economic growth by 0.1% to 3.1% in 2016 and 3.4% in 2017, as a result of the referendum, which it said had "thrown a spanner in the works" of global recovery.<ref>{{cite news|first=Larry |last=Elliott |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/jul/19/imf-cuts-uk-growth-forecasts-following-brexit-vote |title=IMF cuts UK growth forecasts following Brexit vote |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 July 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>

On 20 July, a report released by the [[Bank of England]] said that although uncertainty had risen "markedly" since the referendum, it was yet to see evidence of a sharp economic decline as a consequence. However, around a third of contacts surveyed for the report expected there to be "some negative impact" over the following year.<ref>{{cite news|first=Lucy |last=Meakin |first2=Jill |last2=Ward |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-20/boe-sees-no-sharp-slowing-yet-even-as-brexit-boosts-uncertainty |title=BOE Sees No Sharp Slowing Yet Even as Brexit Boosts Uncertainty |work=Bloomberg News |publisher=Bloomberg |date=20 July 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref>

In September 2016, following three months of positive economic data after the referendum, commentators suggested that many of the negative statements and predictions promoted from within the "remain" camp had failed to materialise,<ref name="The Times 2016-09-02">{{cite news|last=Ralph|first=Alex|title=''Rally rewards bravery in the face of Project Fear''|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/rally-rewards-bravery-in-the-face-of-project-fear-tkdz2h95n|date=2 September 2016|publisher=The Times|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref> but by December, analysis began to show that Brexit was having an effect on inflation.<ref>{{cite web|author=Katie Allen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/dec/21/brexit-economy-referendum-inflation-uk-2017 |title=Brexit economy: inflation surge shows impact of vote finally beginning to bite &#124; Business |publisher=The Guardian |date=22 November 2016 |accessdate=5 March 2017}}</ref>

In April 2017 the IMF raised their forecast for the UK economy from 1.5% to 2% for 2017 and from 1.4% to 1.5% for 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.sky.com/story/imf-raises-forecast-for-uk-economic-growth-to-2-in-2017-10842188 |title=IMF raises forecast for UK economic growth to 2% in 2017 |publisher=Sky News |date=18 April 2017}}</ref>

==Party politics==

===Conservative===
[[file:David cameron annouces resignation.jpg|thumb|right|Prime Minister David Cameron announces his resignation following the outcome of the referendum]]
{{further|Conservative Party (UK) leadership election, 2016}}

On 24 June, the Conservative Party leader and prime minister, [[David Cameron]], announced that he would resign by October because the Leave campaign had been successful in the referendum.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36615028|title=Brexit: David Cameron to quit after UK votes to leave EU|date=24 June 2016|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> Although most of the Conservative MPs on both sides of the referendum debate had urged him to stay, the [[UK Independence Party|UKIP]] leader, [[Nigel Farage]], called for Cameron to go "immediately".<ref>{{cite web|title = Brexit: David Cameron to quit after UK votes to leave EU|publisher=BBC New|date=24 June 2015|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36615028|accessdate=24 June 2016}}</ref> A leadership election was scheduled for 9 September, with the new leader to be in place before the party's autumn conference on 2 October.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36640889 |title=New Tory leader 'should be in place by 9 September' |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=28 June 2016 |publisher=BBC News  |access-date=29 June 2016}}</ref> The two main candidates were predicted to be [[Boris Johnson]], who had been a keen supporter of leaving the EU, and [[Home Secretary]] [[Theresa May]], who had campaigned for Remain.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/25/theresa-may-emerges-as-stop-boris-tory-leadership-candidate|title=Theresa May emerges as 'Stop Boris' Tory leadership candidate|newspaper=The Guardian|date=25 June 2016|author=Rowena Mason|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref> The last-minute candidature by Johnson's former ally [[Michael Gove]] destabilised the race and forced Johnson to stand down; the final two candidates became May and [[Andrea Leadsom]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/conservative-leadership-andrea-leadsom-emerges-to-rival-theresa-may-a7114916.html|title=Conservative leadership: Andrea Leadsom emerges as pro-Leave rival to Theresa May as Michael Gove fades|date=2 July 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref><ref name="SecondBallot">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36737426|title=Theresa May v Andrea Leadsom in Conservative leader race|publisher=BBC News  }}</ref> Leadsom soon withdrew, leaving May as new party leader and next prime minister.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-36768148|title=PM-in-waiting Theresa May promises 'a better Britain'|date=11 July 2016|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> She took office on 13 July.<ref>{{cite news|first=Kylie |last=MacLellan |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-may-idUKKCN0ZT20C |title=After winning power, Theresa May faces Brexit divorce battle |agency=Reuters |date=13 July 2016 |accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>

===Labour===
{{further|Labour Party (UK) leadership election, 2016}}
The Labour Party leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] faced growing criticism from his [[Parliamentary Labour Party|parliamentary party]] MPs, who had supported remaining within the EU, for poor campaigning,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1716177/labour-out-votes-heap-pressure-on-corbyn|title=Labour 'Out' Votes Heap Pressure on Corbyn}}</ref> and two Labour MPs submitted a vote of [[no confidence]] in Corbyn on 24 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/live/uk-politics-36570120|title=Brexit after EU referendum: UK to leave EU and David Cameron quits|accessdate=24 June 2016}}</ref> It is claimed that there is evidence that Corbyn deliberately sabotaged Labour's campaign to remain part of the EU, despite remain polling favourably among Labour voters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36633238|title=Corbyn office 'sabotaged' EU Remain campaign|accessdate= 26 June 2016}}</ref> In the early hours of Sunday 26 June, Corbyn sacked [[Hilary Benn]] (the shadow foreign secretary) for apparently leading a coup against him. This led to a string of Labour MPs quickly resigning their roles in the party.<ref>{{cite news|title=Labour in crisis: Tom Watson criticises Hilary Benn sacking|work=The Guardian|author=Asthana A |author2=Syal, R.|accessdate=26 June 2016|date=26 June 2016|url=http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/labour-in-crisis-tom-watson-criticises-hilary-benn-sacking/ar-AAhDKv3?li=BBoPWjQ&ocid=SL5MDHP}}</ref> By mid-afternoon on 27 June 2016, 23 of the Labour Party's 31 shadow cabinet members had resigned from the shadow cabinet as had seven parliamentary private secretaries. On 27 June 2016, Corbyn filled some of the vacancies and was working to fill the others.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Jeremy Corbyn's new-look shadow cabinet |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/28/labour-crisis-vote-jeremy-corbyn-leadership-david-cameron-brexit/ |newspaper=The Telegraph |location=London, UK |date=27 June 2016 |access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref>

According to a source quoted by the BBC, the party's Deputy Leader [[Tom Watson (Labour politician)|Tom Watson]] told leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] that "it looks like we are moving towards a leadership election." Corbyn stated that he would run again in that event.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36638041 |title=Corbyn told he faces leadership fight as resignations continue |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=27 June 2016 |publisher=BBC News  |access-date=27 June 2016 |quote=Deputy Labour leader Tom Watson has told Jeremy Corbyn he has "no authority" among Labour MPs and warned him he faces a leadership challenge.}}</ref> A no confidence motion was held on 28 June 2016; Corbyn lost the motion with more than 80% (172) of MPs voting against him with a turnout of 95%.<ref>{{cite news|title=Jeremy Corbyn Loses Vote of No Confidence|publisher=Sky News|date=28 June 2016|access-date=28 June 2016|url=http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/jeremy-corbyn-loses-vote-of-no-confidence/ar-AAhJ3KO?li=BBoPWjQ&ocid=SL5MDHP|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160701173053/http://www.msn.com/en-gb/news/uknews/jeremy-corbyn-loses-vote-of-no-confidence/ar-AAhJ3KO?li=BBoPWjQ&ocid=SL5MDHP|archivedate=1 July 2016}}</ref>

Corbyn responded with a statement that the motion had no "constitutional legitimacy" and that he intended to continue as the elected leader. The vote does not require the party to call a leadership election<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-wrapup-idUSKCN0ZE11Y |title=EU leaders tell Britain to exit swiftly, market rout halts |last1=Holden |first1=Michael |last2=Piper |first2=Elizabeth |date=28 June 2016 |agency=Reuters |access-date=28 June 2016 |quote=the confidence vote does not automatically trigger a leadership election and Corbyn, who says he enjoys strong grassroots support, refused to quit. 'I was democratically elected leader of our party for a new kind of politics by 60 percent of Labour members and supporters, and I will not betray them by resigning,' he said.}}</ref> but, according to ''[[The Guardian]]'': "the result is likely to lead to a direct challenge to Corbyn as some politicians scramble to collect enough nominations to trigger a formal challenge to his leadership."<ref>{{cite news |last=Asthana |first=Anushka |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/28/jeremy-corbyn-loses-labour-mps-confidence-vote |title=Jeremy Corbyn suffers heavy loss in Labour MPs confidence vote |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London, UK |date=28 June 2016|access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> By 29 June, Corbyn had been encouraged to resign by Labour Party stalwarts such as Dame [[Tessa Jowell]], [[Ed Miliband]] and Dame [[Margaret Beckett]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Wilkinson |first=Michael |date=29 June 2016 |title=David Cameron and Ed Miliband tell Jeremy Corbyn to resign as Tom Watson says he will not contest Labour leadership leaving Angela Eagle as the unity candidate |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/29/jeremy-corbyn-pmqs-labour-angela-eagle-david-cameron-eu-brexit/ |newspaper=The Telegraph |location=London, UK |access-date=29 June 2016}}</ref> Union leaders rallied behind Corbyn, issuing a joint statement saying that the Labour leader had a "resounding mandate" and a leadership election would be an "unnecessary distraction". Supporting Corbyn, [[John McDonnell]] said, "We're not going to be bullied by Labour MPs who refuse to accept democracy in our party."<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36667795 | title=Corbyn to face Labour leadership challenge from Angela Eagle | publisher=BBC | date=29 June 2016 | accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref>

On 11 July, [[Angela Eagle]] announced her campaign for the Labour party leadership after attaining enough support of MPs to trigger a leadership contest, saying that she "can provide the leadership that Corbyn can't".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36761370|title=Labour leadership: Angela Eagle says she can unite the party|date=11 July 2016|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> Eagle subsequently dropped out of the race (on 18 July) leaving [[Owen Smith (politician)|Owen Smith]] as the only contender to [[Jeremy Corbyn]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Grice |first=Andrew |date=19 July 2016 |title=Labour leadership election: Angela Eagle pulls out of contest to allow Owen Smith straight run at Jeremy Corbyn |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/angela-eagle-pulls-out-labour-leadership-election-owen-smith-jeremy-corbyn-a7145021.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London, UK |access-date=19 July 2016}}</ref>

Smith had supported the campaign for Britain to [[Britain Stronger in Europe|remain]] in the [[European Union]], in the [[United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016|referendum on Britain's membership]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-35616946|title=EU vote: Where the cabinet and other MPs stand|date=22 June 2016|publisher=BBC News}}</ref> On 13 July 2016, following the vote to [[United Kingdom withdrawal from the European Union|leave]] the EU, three weeks prior, he pledged that he would press for an early general election or offer a further referendum on the final 'Brexit' deal drawn up by the [[Theresa May|new prime minister]], were he to be elected [[Leader of the Labour Party (UK)|Labour leader]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/13/owen-smith-to-offer-referendum-on-brexit-deal-if-elected-labour-leader|title=Owen Smith to offer referendum on Brexit deal if elected Labour leader|date=13 July 2016|authors=Anushka Asthana, Heather Stewart|work=The Guardian}}</ref>

Approximately two weeks later, Smith told the BBC that (in his view) those who had voted with the Leave faction had done so "because they felt a sense of loss in their communities, decline, cuts that have hammered away at vital public services and they haven't felt that any politicians, certainly not the politicians they expect to stand up for them..." His recommendation was to "put in place concrete policies that will bring real improvements to people's lives so I'm talking about a British New Deal for every part of Britain..."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-wales-politics-36860780 |title=Owen Smith on Corbyn, leadership, devolution and Brexit |last=Cornock |first=David |date=21 July 2016 |publisher=BBC Wales |access-date=25 July 2016 |quote=said voters backed Brexit because they didn't feel the Labour Party stood up for them,}}</ref>

===Liberal Democrats===
The [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Lib Dems]], who are a strongly [[pro-Europeanism|pro-European]] party, announced that they respect the referendum result, but would make remaining in the EU a [[Party platform|manifesto]] pledge at the next election.<ref name="Farron">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/26/lib-dems-pledge-british-return-eu-next-general-election|title=Lib Dems to pledge British return to EU in next general election |date=26 June 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref> Leader [[Tim Farron]] said that "The British people deserve the chance not to be stuck with the appalling consequences of a leave campaign that stoked that anger with the lies of Farage, Johnson and Gove."<ref name="Farron"/>

===More United===
In reaction to the lack of unified pro-EU voice following the referendum, members of the Liberal Democrats and others discussed the launch of a new centre-left political movement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wintour|first1=Patrick|title=Liberals, celebrities and EU supporters set up progressive movement|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/19/liberals-celebrities-and-eu-supporters-set-up-progressive-movement|accessdate=24 July 2016|date=19 July 2016|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> This was officially launched on 24 June as [[More United]], named after a line in the [[maiden speech]] of Labour MP [[Jo Cox]], who was [[Killing of Jo Cox|killed during the referendum campaign]].<ref name="BusinessInsider">{{cite news|last1=Shead|first1=Sam|title=Paddy Ashdown has launched a tech-driven political startup called More United that will crowdfund MPs across all parties|url=http://uk.businessinsider.com/paddy-ashdown-has-launched-a-tech-driven-political-startup-called-more-united-2016-7|accessdate=24 July 2016|date=24 July 2016|newspaper=Business Insider}}</ref> More United is a cross-party coalition, and will [[crowdfund]] candidates from any party who support its goals, which include [[environmentalism]], a [[market economy]] with strong [[public services]], and close co-operation with the EU.<ref name="MUPrinciples">{{cite web|url=http://www.moreunited.uk/beliefs|title=Our Principles|website=More Together|accessdate=26 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161116045841/http://www.moreunited.uk/beliefs|archive-date=16 November 2016|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

===UKIP===
{{further|UK Independence Party leadership election, September 2016|UK Independence Party leadership election, November 2016}}

The [[UK Independence Party]] was founded to press for British withdrawal from the EU, and following the referendum its leader [[Nigel Farage]] announced, on 4 July, that having succeeded in this goal, he would stand down as leader.<ref name="BBC News">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36702468|title=UKIP leader Nigel Farage stands down|publisher=BBC News|date=4 July 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref>  Following the resignation of the [[UK Independence Party leadership election, September 2016|elected]] leader [[Diane James]], Farage became the interim party leader on 5 October.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-37561065|title=Nigel Farage steps back in at UKIP as Diane James quits|work=BBC news|date=5 October 2016|accessdate=18 October 2016}}</ref> Farage's successor [[Paul Nuttall]] was [[UK Independence Party leadership election, November 2016|elected]] the party leader on 28 November 2016.<ref name="Fisher1">{{cite news|last1=Fisher|first1=Lucy|title=Putin and Assad are on our side, claims new Ukip leader|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/farages-deputy-wins-ukip-race-and-vows-to-replace-labour-g5bw0xq38|work=The Times|subscription=yes|date=28 November 2016}}</ref>

==General politics==
The government and the [[Civil Service (United Kingdom)|civil service]] is heavily focused on Brexit. Former [[Head of the Home Civil Service]] [[Bob Kerslake]] has stated that there is a risk that other matters will get insufficient attention until they develop into crises.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/global/2017/apr/09/focus-brexit-obliterates-social-policy-agenda  Crisis looms for social policy agenda as Brexit preoccupies Whitehall] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>

A cross party coalition of MP's has been formed to oppose hard Brexit.  This group is known as, the all-party parliamentary group on EU relations.  [[Chuka Umunna]] said that MP's should be active players rather than spectators, he said, “We will be fighting in parliament for a future relationship with the EU that protects our prosperity and rights at work, and which delivers a better and safer world.”<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jul/10/rebel-mps-form-cross-party-group-to-oppose-hard-brexit  Rebel MPs form cross-party group to oppose hard Brexit] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>

===Second general election===
{{further|United Kingdom general election, 2017}}
Under the [[Fixed-term Parliaments Act 2011]], the next general election was scheduled to be held on 7 May 2020.<ref name="When">{{cite news|last1=Tuft|first1=Ben|title=When will the next UK General Election be held?|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/generalelection/when-will-the-next-uk-general-election-be-held-10236102.html|work=The Independent|accessdate=17 August 2015}}</ref>

Following the result of the referendum, some political commentators argued that it might be necessary to hold an early general election before negotiations to leave begin.<ref name=Samuel>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/24/the-eu-referendum-reveals-a-nation-utterly-divided--an-early-gen/ |title=The EU referendum reveals a nation utterly divided.  An early general election is the only answer |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=24 June 2016}}</ref> The final two candidates in the [[Conservative Party (UK) leadership election, 2016|Conservative Party leadership election]] – Andrea Leadsom and Theresa May – said they would not seek an early general election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.eu/article/andrea-leadsom-eu-citizens-can-stay-in-uk/|title=Andrea Leadsom: EU citizens can stay in UK|author=Vince Chadwick|date=4 July 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016|website=politico.eu}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/theresa-may-rules-our-early-general-election-or-second-eu-referendum-if-she-becomes-conservative-a7110656.html|title=Theresa May rules out early general election or second EU referendum if she becomes Conservative leader|author=Jon Stone|date=30 June 2016|accessdate=6 July 2016|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref> However, after Leadsom's withdrawal and with May thus due to become prime minister without any broader vote, there were renewed calls for an early election from commentators<ref>''Daily Politics'', BBC2, 11 July 2016</ref> and politicians. [[Tim Farron]], leader of the Liberal Democrats, called for an early election shortly after Leadsom's withdrawal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-36570120|title=David Cameron's last full day as PM and Labour leadership|date=12 July 2016|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref>

Despite repeatedly previously ruling out an early General Election, May announced on 18 April 2017 her intention to call an election on 8 June 2017. This required a  two-thirds super-majority of the Commons in support of a motion for an early general election, which was agreed on 19 April.  May stated that "division in Westminster will risk ability to make a success of Brexit and it will cause damaging uncertainty and instability to the country... We need a general election and we need one now, because we have at this moment a one-off chance to get this done while the European Union agrees its negotiating position and before the detailed talks begin. I have only recently and reluctantly come to this conclusion."<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2017-04-18/general-election-theresa-mays-statement-in-full/|title=Theresa May's surprise General Election statement in full|last=|first=|date=18 April 2017|work=|access-date=18 April 2017}}</ref>

The snap election resulted in an unexpected [[Hung Parliament]] with the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservatives]] losing their overall majority but remained as the largest party which has led to further political turmoil.

===Pressure groups===
{{main|Opposition to Brexit in the United Kingdom}}
Numerous pressure groups were established after the referendum to oppose Brexit.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jan/10/brexit-resistance-getting-bigger-pro-europe-eu-referendum-organising-groups The Brexit resistance: ‘It’s getting bigger all the time’] ''[[The Guardian]]''</ref>

===Former prime ministers' views===
A week after the referendum, [[Gordon Brown]], a former Labour prime minister who had [[Signing of the Treaty of Lisbon#Absence of Gordon Brown|signed the Lisbon Treaty]] in 2007, warned of a danger that in the next decade the country would be refighting the referendum. He wrote that remainers were feeling they must be pessimists to prove that Brexit is unmanageable without catastrophe, while leavers optimistically claim economic risks are exaggerated.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brown|first1=Gordon|title=The key lesson of Brexit is that globalisation must work for all of Britain|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jun/29/key-lesson-of-brexit-globalisation-must-work-for-all-of-britain|accessdate=18 November 2016|work=The Guardian|date=29 June 2016}}</ref>

The previous Labour prime minister, [[Tony Blair]], in October 2016 called for a second referendum, a decision through parliament or a general election to decide finally if Britain should leave the EU.<ref>{{cite news|author=Joe Watts Political Editor |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-tony-blair-second-eu-referendum-vote-article-50-latest-a7384411.html |title=Brexit: Tony Blair says there must be a second vote on UK's membership of EU |work=The Independent |date=28 October 2016 |accessdate=9 November 2016}}</ref> Former leader of the Conservative prime minister [[John Major]] argued in November 2016 that parliament will have to ratify whatever deal is negotiated and then, depending on the deal there could be a case for a second referendum.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38092635|title=Tony Blair 'to help the UK's politically homeless'|date=24 November 2016|publisher=|via=www.bbc.co.uk}}</ref>

==Withdrawal negotiations==
{{main|Brexit negotiations}}
In the summer of 2018, a survey by YouGov indicated that five British people think the government is handling negotiations badly for every one who approves of the government's negotiations. In another survery, voters indicated dissatisfaction not only with the UK government. The polling organisation NatCen found 57% think the EU is handling Brexit talks badly, while only 16% believe it is doing well.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-45520517 What British people think about Brexit now] ''[[BBC]]'' 18 September 2018</ref>

===Immigration concerns===
To what extent free movement of people would or would not be retained in any post-Brexit deal with the EU has emerged as a key political issue. Shortly after the result, the Conservative politician [[Daniel Hannan]], who campaigned for Leave, told the BBC's ''[[Newsnight]]'' that Brexit was likely to change little about the freedom of movement between the UK and the European Union, concluding "We never said there was going to be some radical decline ... we want a measure of control."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/eu-referendum-tory-campaigner-admits-brexit-immigration-some-control-a7102626.html|title=Leading Tory Brexiter says 'free movement of Labour' should continue after Brexit|date=25 June 2016|language=en-GB|access-date=25 June 2016|website=The Independent}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/06/tory-brexiter-daniel-hannan-leave-campaign-never-promised-radical-decline|title=Tory Brexiter Daniel Hannan: Leave campaign never promised "radical decline" in immigration|website=New Statesman|access-date=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36628894 |title=Newsnight exchange with Brexit MEP Daniel Hannan |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=25 June 2016 |publisher=BBC News |access-date=26 June 2016}}</ref><ref>"Frankly, if people watching think that they have voted and there is now going to be zero immigration from the EU, they are going to be disappointed ... you will look in vain for anything that the Leave campaign said at any point that ever suggested there would ever be any kind of border closure or drawing up of the drawbridge." {{cite web |url=https://inews.co.uk/essentials/news/leave-campaigners-suggest-pledges-may-not-upheld/ |title=Nigel Farage: Leave campaign pledges 'mistake', may not be upheld |last=Lowyry |first=Nigel |date=25 June 2016 |website=iNews UK |publisher=Media Nusantara Citra |access-date=26 June 2016}}</ref>

Theresa May stated in August 2016 that leaving the EU 'must mean controls on the numbers of people who come to Britain from Europe but also a positive outcome for those who wish to trade goods and services'.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/aug/31/restricting-immigration-will-be-at-heart-of-brexit-deal-theresa-may-says|title=Restricting immigration will be at heart of Brexit deal, Theresa May says|date=31 August 2016|journal=The Guardian|last1=Anushka|first1=Asthana}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/may/14/brexit-what-would-happen-if-britain-left-eu-european-union-referendum-uk|title=Brexit – what would happen if Britain left the EU?|last2=Oltermann|first2=Philip|date=14 May 2015|journal=The Guardian|last3=Borger|first3=Julian|last4=Neslen|first4=Arthur|last1=Allen|first1=Katie}}</ref> According to a Home Office document leaked in September 2017, Britain plans to end the free movement of labour immediately after Brexit and introduce restrictions to deter all but highly skilled EU workers. It proposes offering low-skilled workers residency for a maximum of two years and the highly skilled work permits for three to five years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/sep/05/leaked-document-reveals-uk-brexit-plan-to-deter-eu-immigrants|title=Leaked document reveals UK Brexit plan to deter EU immigrants|last=Hopkins|first=Nick|date=5 September 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=|last2=Travis|first2=Alan}}</ref>

[[Boris Johnson]] initially argued that restricting freedom of movement was not one of the main reasons why people have voted Leave, but his position was seen as too lax on the issue by other Conservative Party Leave supporters, which may have contributed to [[Michael Gove]]'s decision to stand for the party's leadership contest.<ref>{{Cite newspaper|author=Laura Hughes |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/30/boris-johnson-wont-run-for-prime-minister-after-michael-gove-ent/ |title=Conservative MPs in uproar as Boris Johnson 'rips party apart' by withdrawing from leadership contest after ambush by Michael Gove |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=31 May 2016 |accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref> Meanwhile, EU leaders warned that full access to the single market would not be available without retaining free movement of people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/europe/21701448-many-brussels-still-hope-article-50-will-be-delayed-indefinitely-european-union |title=The European Union has agreed on two important questions regarding Brexit |work=The Economist |accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref> Limitations on the free movement of EU citizens within the UK will also have [[Effects of Brexit on research and innovation policy|consequences for research and innovation]]. While campaigning in the [[Conservative Party (UK) leadership election, 2016|Conservative leadership contest]], Gove pledged to end the freedom of movement accord with the EU and instead implement an Australian-style points system.<ref>{{cite web | last1=Hickson | first1=Alex | title=Michael Gove Gets Tough with 'Aussie Rules' Immigration but No Article 50 Until Next Year | url=http://www.dailystar.co.uk/news/latest-news/526956/Michael-Gove-Conservative-Australia-point-system-Brexit-Europe-migration-Article-50 | date=1 July 2016 | work=Daily Star|location=United Kingdom | accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>

[[Natacha Bouchart|Natasha Bouchard]], the Mayor of [[Calais]], suggests that the government of France should renegotiate the [[Juxtaposed controls|Le Touquet treaty]], which allows British border guards to check trains, cars and lorries before they cross the Channel from France to Britain and therefore to keep irregular immigrants away from Britain.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-immigration-le-touquet-treaty-border-control-calais-mayor-france-migrants-a7101776.html|title=Calais Mayor says France should reconsider treaty stopping migrants getting to Dover|date=24 June 2016|language=en-GB|access-date=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite newspaper|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36626553|title=EU Brexit referendum: France's Calais seeks border deal changes|journal=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=25 June 2016|date=2016-06-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3659052/Mayor-Calais-calls-migrant-camps-moved-Britain-Brexit-vote-scuppers-border-deal-France.html|title=Jungle residents claim Brexit will help them sneak into the UK|access-date=25 June 2016|date=2016-06-24}}</ref> French government officials doubt that the trilateral agreement (it includes Belgium) would be valid after the UK has officially left the European Union and especially think that it is unlikely that there will be any political motivation to enforce the agreement.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/eu-referendum-the-truth-about-the-calais-jungle-s-fate-in-the-event-of-brexit-a6861761.html|title=The truth about the Calais Jungle's fate in the event of Brexit|date=8 February 2016|language=en-GB|access-date=25 June 2016}}</ref> However, on 1 July 2016 [[François Hollande]] said British border controls would stay in place in France, though France suggested during the referendum campaign they would be scrapped allowing migrants in the "[[Calais Jungle|Jungle]]" camp easy access to Kent.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3670117/France-admits-WON-T-scrap-deal-keeps-British-border-Jungle-camp-Calais-despite-threats-Brexit-referendum.html|title=France WON'T scrap a deal that keeps the British border in Calais|access-date=2 July 2016|date=July 2016}}</ref>

In late July 2016, discussions were underway that might provide the UK with an exemption from the EU rules on refugees' freedom of movement for up to seven years. Senior UK government sources confirmed to ''[[The Observer]]'' that this was "certainly one of the ideas now on the table".<ref>{{cite news |last=Helm |first=Toby |date=24 July 2016 |title=Brexit: EU considers migration 'emergency brake' for UK for up to seven years |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jul/24/brexit-deal-free-movement-exemption-seven-years |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London, UK |access-date=24 July 2016}}</ref> If the discussions led to an agreement, the UK – though not an EU member – would also retain access to the single market but would be required to pay a significant annual contribution to the EU. According to ''The Daily Telegraph'' the news of this possibility caused a rift in the Conservative Party: "Tory MPs have reacted with fury ... [accusing European leaders of] ... failing to accept the public's decision to sever ties with the 28-member bloc last month."<ref>{{cite news |last=Hughes |first=Laura |date=24 July 2016 |title=Tory MPs react with fury as EU leaders consider UK 'emergency brake' on free movement |newspaper=The Telegraph |location=London, UK }}</ref>

According to CEP analysis of Labour Force Survey, immigrants in the UK are on average more educated than UK-born citizens. Citizens in the UK are concerned that immigrants are taking over their jobs since most immigrants are highly educated, however, they are actually helping the economy because they too consume goods, and produce jobs.<ref>{{cite journal|last2=Dhingra|first2=Swati|last3=Ottaviano|first3=Gianmarco|last4=John|first4=Van Reenen|title=Brexit and the Impact of Immigration on the UK|url=http://cep.lse.ac.uk/pubs/download/brexit05.pdf|last1=Wadsworth|first1=Jonathan|accessdate=15 November 2016}}</ref> Immigrants to the UK help to mitigate the negative effects of the ageing British labour force and are believed to have an overall net positive fiscal effect. Some have argued that immigration has a dampening effect on wages due to the greater supply of labour.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Brexit and Immigration|journal=Economic Outlook|volume=40|issue=2|page=20|doi=10.1111/1468-0319.12215|year=2016}}</ref> However, other studies suggest that immigration has only a small impact on the average wage of workers. Immigration may have a negative impact on the wages of low-skilled workers but can push up the wages of medium- and highly paid workers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fullfact.org/immigration/immigration-and-jobs-labour-market-effects-immigration/|title=How immigrants affect jobs and wages|last=|first=|date=15 May 2017|website=Full Fact|access-date=}}</ref>

===Status of current EU immigrants and British emigrants===
There were about 3.7&nbsp;million EU citizens (including Irish) living in the UK in 2016 and around 1.2&nbsp;million British citizens living in other EU countries.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=https://fullfact.org/immigration/eu-migration-and-uk/|title=EU immigration to the UK|website=Full Fact|date=22 June 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref> The future status of both groups of people and their reciprocal rights are the object of Brexit negotiations.<ref name="urged">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/03/leave-remain-letter-tories-eu-citizens-uk|title=Tories urged to offer assurances to EU citizens living in UK|author=Mark Tran|newspaper=The Observer|date=3 July 2016}}</ref> According to the British Office for National Statistics, 623,000 EU citizens came to live in England and Wales before 1981. A further 855,000 arrived before the year 2000. As of 2017, approximately 1.4 million Eastern Europeans were living in Britain, including 916,000 Poles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/jul/10/majority-of-britain-eastern-european-residents-are-in-work|title=80% of Britain's 1.4m eastern European residents are in work|last=Travis|first=Alan|date=10 July 2017|website=|access-date=}}</ref> In May 2004, when the EU welcomed ten new member states from a majority of Central and Eastern European countries, the UK was one of only three EU member states, alongside Sweden and Ireland, to open their labour market immediately to these new EU citizens.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://theconversation.com/the-huge-political-cost-of-blairs-decision-to-allow-eastern-european-migrants-unfettered-access-to-britain-66077|title=The huge political cost of Blair’s decision to allow Eastern European migrants unfettered access to Britain|last=Consterdine|first=Erica|date=16 November 2016|website=The Conversation|access-date=}}</ref> In the 12 months following the referendum, the estimated number of EU nationals immigrating to the UK fell from 284,000 to 230,000. In parallel, the number of EU citizens emigrating from the UK increased from an estimated 95,000 in the year before the vote to 123,000. Annual net immigration from the EU to the UK has, thus, fallen to about 100,000.<ref name=":0" />

Theresa May, when candidate for Conservative leader, suggested that the status of EU immigrants currently in the UK could be used in negotiations with other European countries, with the possibility of expelling these people if the EU does not offer favourable exit terms.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/07/theresa-may-want-kick-europeans/|title=Is Theresa May really threatening to deport Europeans?|newspaper=The Spectator|date=3 July 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016|author=Fraser Nelson}}</ref> This position has been strongly rejected by other politicians from both Remain and Leave campaigns.<ref name="urged"/> In response to a question by [[Labour Leave]] campaigner [[Gisela Stuart]], the [[Minister for Security and Immigration]] [[James Brokenshire]] said that the Government was unable to make any promises about the status of EU citizens in the UK before the government had set out negotiating positions, and that it would seek reciprocal protection for UK citizens in EU countries.<ref>{{cite news|title=Immigration minister says it would be 'unwise' to promise EU nationals now they can stay in UK|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jul/04/brexit-live-plan-leave-vote-hysteria-boris-johnson?page=with:block-577a752ce4b05db362ab758d#block-577a752ce4b05db362ab758d|date=4 July 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|author=Andrew Sparrow and Claire Phipps}}</ref>

The [[Vice-Chancellor of Germany]], [[Sigmar Gabriel]], announced that the country would consider easing citizenship requirements for British nationals currently in Germany, to protect their status.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/germany-should-offer-young-brits-eu-citizenship-following-brexit-says-german-vice-chancellor-a7116881.html|title=Germany should offer young Britons EU citizenship after Brexit, says German Vice-Chancellor|newspaper=The Independent|author=Rachel Pells|date=3 July 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref> The foreign ministry of Ireland stated that the number of applications from UK citizens for Irish passports increased significantly after the announcement of the result of the referendum on the membership in the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/24/brexit-scramble-for-european-passports|title=Brexit vote sparks scramble for European passports|last=Harding|first=Luke|date=24 June 2016|website=The Guardian|access-date=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="ABC News Passports 2016">{{cite web | title=Brexit vote sparks surge in Irish passport applications | publisher=ABC News | date=27 June 2016 | url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-06-28/brexit-vote-sparks-surge-in-irish-passport-applications/7548710 | accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> The [[Embassy of Ireland, London|Irish Embassy in London]] usually receives 200 passport applications a day, which increased to 4,000 a day after the vote to leave.<ref name="Halpin Reuters 2016">{{cite news | last=Halpin | first=Padraic | title=Britons flood Ireland with EU passport queries after Brexit vote | agency=Reuters | date=27 June 2016 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-ireland-passports-idUSKCN0ZD1KA | accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref> Other EU nations also had increases in requests for passports from British citizens, including France and Belgium.<ref name="Halpin Reuters 2016" />

===EU funding===
{{see also|Brexit and arrangements for science and technology}}
[[Cornwall]] voted to leave the EU but [[Cornwall Council]] issued a plea for protection of its local economy and to continue receiving subsidies, as it had received millions of pounds in subsidies from the EU.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/brexit-cornwall-issues-plea-for-funding-protection-after-county-overwhelmingly-votes-in-favour-of-a7101311.html#|title=Cornwall votes for Brexit then pleads to keep EU funding|website=The Independent|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=25 June 2016|last=Worley|first=Will}}</ref>

After the referendum, leading scientists expressed fear of a shortfall in funding for research and science and worried that the UK had become less attractive for scientists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/6/24/12023772/brexit-vote-uk-science-terrified|title=Why the Brexit vote result has UK scientists terrified|last=Resnick|first=Brian|date=24 June 2016|website=Vox|access-date=25 June 2016}}</ref> The UK science minister, [[Jo Johnson]] said the government would be on the watch for discrimination against UK scientists, after stories circulated about scientists being left out of joint grant proposals with other EU scientists in the aftermath of the referendum.<ref>{{cite web|author=Tania Rabesandratana |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/news/2016/06/science-minister-says-hes-watching-out-post-brexit-discrimination-against-uk |title=Science minister says he's watching out for post-Brexit 'discrimination' against U.K. researchers &#124; AAAS |doi=10.1126/science.aaf5826 |publisher=Sciencemag.org |accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref>
On 15 August 2016, ministers announced that research funding would be matched by the UK government.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cressey|first=Daniel|title=''UK government gives Brexit science funding guarantee''|url=http://www.nature.com/news/uk-government-gives-brexit-science-funding-guarantee-1.20434|date=15 August 2016|publisher=Nature|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref>

In October 2016, government ministers announced that the UK would be investing 220 million pounds ($285 million) in support of the nation's technology industry.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rascouet|first=Angelina|title=''U.K. Unveils $285 Million Funding to Boost Technology Industry''|date=1 October 2016|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref> The [[consequences of Brexit for academia]] will become clearer once negotiations for Britain's post-Brexit relationship with the EU get under way.

The [[European Union Youth Orchestra]] announced in October 2017 that, as a result of [[Brexit]], it intends to relocate from London to Italy. It is expected British youth will cease being eligible to participate in the orchestra in future.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brown |first=Mark |date= 11 October 2017 |title=EU youth orchestra to quit UK for Italy over Brexit |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/oct/11/eu-youth-orchestra-to-quit-uk-for-italy-over-brexit |work=[[The Guardian]] |location=[[London]] |access-date=11 October 2017}}</ref>

===British participation in European institutions===
{{see also|Brexit and arrangements for science and technology}}As of January 2018, the European Commission had announced that three European agencies would be leaving the UK as a consequence of its withdrawal from the EU: the [[European Medicines Agency]], [[European Banking Authority]] and the [[Galileo Satellite Monitoring Agency]].

===Republic of Ireland–United Kingdom border===
{{further|Republic of Ireland–United Kingdom border}}
The United Kingdom and the [[Republic of Ireland]] are members of the [[Common Travel Area]], which allows free movement between these countries. If the UK negotiates a settlement with the EU that does not involve Freedom of Movement, while the Republic of Ireland remains an EU member, an open border between the Republic and Northern Ireland is likely to become untenable.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ireland fears return to bad old days of borders|author=Vincent Boland|newspaper=Financial Times|date=4 July 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/efe1d3ca-3fa4-11e6-9f2c-36b487ebd80a.html}}</ref> Martin McGuinness, deputy First Minister of Northern Ireland, said this would "seriously undermine" the [[Good Friday Agreement]] that brought an end to [[the Troubles]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/homenews/14594938.Martin_McGuinness__Brexit___39_seriously_undermines__39__Good_Friday_Agreement/|title=Martin McGuinness: Brexit 'seriously undermines' Good Friday Agreement|date=24 June 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016|newspaper=The Herald|location=Glasgow}}</ref> David Cameron pledged to do whatever possible to maintain the open border.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/david-cameron-pledges-whatever-help-he-can-to-keep-northern-irish-border-407644.html|title=David Cameron pledges 'whatever help he can' to keep Northern Irish border|author=Elaine Loughlin|date=30 June 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016|newspaper=Irish Examiner}}</ref> Since becoming prime minister Theresa May has reassured both Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland that there will not be a "hard (customs or immigration) border" on the island of Ireland.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=O'Leary|first=Brendan|year=2016|title=What May Not Happen in UKexit|url=|journal=Inter economics|volume=40|pages=243–244|via=}}</ref>

===Notification of intention to leave the EU (Article 50)===
{{main|United Kingdom invocation of Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union}}
The most likely way that exit from the EU is activated is through [[Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union]]. The British government chooses when to invoke, although theoretically the other members of the European Union could refuse to negotiate before invocation.<ref name="auto3">"It is entirely up to the departing member state to trigger article 50, by issuing formal notification of intention to leave: no one, in Brussels, Berlin or Paris, can force it to. But equally, there is nothing in article 50 that obliges the EU to start talks – including the informal talks the Brexit leaders want – before formal notification has been made. 'There is no mechanism to compel a state to withdraw from the European Union,' said Kenneth Armstrong, professor of European law at Cambridge University.... 'The notification of article 50 is a formal act and has to be done by the British government to the European council,' an EU official told Reuters." {{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/26/who-will-dare-pull-trigger-article-50-eu|title=Will Article 50 ever be triggered?|author=Jon Henley|date=26 June 2016|newspaper=The Observer|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref> This will be the first time that this article has been invoked.  The government can theoretically ignore the result of the referendum.<ref>{{cite news |last=Siddique |first=Haroon |date=23 June 2016 |title=Is the EU referendum legally binding? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/23/eu-referendum-legally-binding-brexit-lisbon-cameron-sovereign-parliament |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London, UK |access-date=26 June 2016}}</ref>

Although Cameron had previously announced that he would invoke Article 50 on the morning after a Leave vote, he declared during his resignation that the next prime minister should activate Article 50 and begin negotiations with the EU.<ref name="Cooper">{{cite news |last=Cooper |first=Charlie |date=27 June 2016 |title=David Cameron rules out second EU referendum after Brexit |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-what-is-eu-referendum-petition-david-cameron-a7105596.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London, UK |access-date=27 June 2016}}</ref> During the Conservative leadership contest, Theresa May expressed that the UK needs a clear negotiating position before triggering Article 50, and that she would not do so in 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-politics-idUSKCN0ZJ0EP|title=Top candidates to lead Britain differ on Brexit urgency|author=Estelle Shirbon and Paul Sandle|date=3 July 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref> The other 27 members of the EU issued a joint statement on 26 June 2016 regretting but respecting Britain's decision and asking them to proceed quickly in accordance with Article 50.<ref>The statement also added: "We stand ready to launch negotiations swiftly with the United Kingdom regarding the terms and conditions of its withdrawal from the European Union. Until this process of negotiations is over, the United Kingdom remains a member of the European Union, with all the rights and obligations that derive from this. According to the Treaties which the United Kingdom has ratified, EU law continues to apply to the full to and in the United Kingdom until it is no longer a Member." {{cite web |url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2016/06/24-joint-statement-uk-referendum/ |title=Statement by the EU leaders and the Netherlands Presidency on the outcome of the UK referendum |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=26 June 2016 |website=European Council |publisher=European Union |access-date=26 June 2016 |quote=We now expect the United Kingdom government to give effect to this decision of the British people as soon as possible, however painful that process may be.}}</ref> This was echoed by the EU Economic Affairs Commissioner [[Pierre Moscovici]].<ref>"There needs to be a notification by the country concerned of its intention to leave (the EU), hence the request (to British prime minister David Cameron) to act quickly." {{cite web |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/international/britain-must-quickly-announce-exit-from-eu-commissioner-116062600648_1.html |title=Britain must 'quickly' announce exit from EU: Commissioner |author=AFP PTI <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=26 June 2016 |website=Business Standard |publisher=Business Standard Private Ltd. |access-date=26 June 2016 |quote=The nation must notify Brussels of its intention to avoid prolonged uncertainty, EU's economic affairs commissioner said}}</ref> However, with the [[French presidential election, 2017|next French presidential election]] being held in April and May 2017, and the [[German federal election, 2017|next German federal election]] likely to be held in autumn 2017, "people close to the E.U. Commission" were reported as saying that the [[European Commission]] was at the time working under the assumption that Article 50 notification would not be made before September 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://global.handelsblatt.com/breaking/sources-european-commission-doesnt-expect-britain-to-apply-to-leave-e-u-before-september-2017|title=Sources: European Commission Doesn’t Expect Britain to Apply to Leave E.U. Before September 2017|newspaper=Handelsblatt|date=5 July 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>

On 27 June 2016, a "Brexit unit" of civil servants were tasked with "intensive work on the issues that will need to be worked through in order to present options and advice to a new Prime Minister and a new Cabinet",<ref>Quote from the PM's spokesperson {{cite news |last=Proctor |first=Kate |date=27 June 2016 |title=Cameron sets up Brexit unit |url=http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/politics/cameron-sets-up-brexit-unit-1-7984750 |newspaper=Yorkshire Post |location=West Yorkshire, UK |access-date=27 June 2016}} Originally headed by [[Oliver Letwin]] for the first eight days</ref> while on 14 July, [[David Davis (British politician)|David Davis]] was appointed to the newly created post of [[Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union]], or "Brexit Secretary", with a remit to oversee the UK's negotiations for withdrawing from the EU.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36785814 |title=Theresa May's cabinet: Who's in and who's out? |publisher=BBC News  |date=14 July 2016 |accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> Davis called for a "brisk but measured" approach to negotiations, and suggested the UK should be ready to trigger Article 50 "before or by the start of" 2017, saying "the first order of business" should be to negotiate trade deals with countries outside the European Union. However, [[Oliver Letwin]], a former [[Minister of State for Europe]], warned the UK had no trade negotiators to lead such talks.<ref name=BBC-Davis>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-uk-leaves-the-eu-36802756 |title=David Davis: Trigger Brexit by start of 2017 |publisher=BBC News  |date=14 July 2016 |accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref>

Having previously ruled out starting the Article 50 process before 2017,<ref name=BBC-Davis/> on 15 July 2016, following a meeting with Scottish First Minister Nicola Sturgeon, May said that it would not begin without a coherent "UK approach" to negotiations.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jon |last=Stone |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-theresa-may-article-50-activated-uk-approach-eu-referendum-scotland-sturgeon-a7138971.html |title=Brexit: Theresa May says Article 50 will not be activated before 'UK approach' decided |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=15 July 2016 |accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> Lawyers representing the government in a legal challenge over the Article 50 process said that May would not trigger Article 50 before 2017.<ref name="BBC hearing">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36834743 |title=October court date for Brexit challenge |publisher=BBC News  |date=19 July 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> However, in September 2016, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' highlighted the lack of coherent strategy following what it described as the "hurricane-strength political wreckage" left by the Brexit vote. It said the public still had no idea what the oft repeated "Brexit means Brexit" meant and there have been nearly as many statements on what the objectives were as there are cabinet ministers.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/what-does-brexit-mean-with-divorce-talks-looming-britain-still-doesnt-have-a-clue/2016/09/16/b2cb7718-79d1-11e6-8064-c1ddc8a724bb_story.html|title=What does Brexit mean? With divorce talks looming, Britain still doesn’t have a clue.|author= Griff Witte|work=Washington Post|date=17 September 2016|accessdate=18 September 2016}}</ref>

The [[Supreme Court of the United Kingdom|Supreme Court]] ruled in [[R (Miller and Dos Santos) v Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union|the Miller case]] in January 2017 that the government needed parliamentary approval to trigger Article 50.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-international/U.K.-govt.-must-get-Parliament-nod-for-Brexit-Supreme-Court/article17091086.ece|title=U.K. govt. must get Parliament nod for Brexit: Supreme Court|last=Ram|first=Vidya|work=The Hindu|access-date=8 March 2017|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Bowcott|first1=Owen|last2=Mason|first2=Rowena|last3=Asthana|first3=Anushka|title=Supreme court rules parliament must have vote to trigger article 50|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/jan/24/supreme-court-brexit-ruling-parliament-vote-article-50|accessdate=9 February 2017|publisher=The Guardian|date=24 January 2017}}</ref><!-- Note to editors: please do not repeat decisions of houses of Parliament here in this section, which is about legal implications. The votes are well reported elsewhere in the article. -->  After the House of Commons overwhelmingly voted, on 1 February 2017, for the government's bill authorising the prime minister to invoke Article 50,<ref name=house-trigger>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-38833883|title=Brexit: MPs overwhelmingly back Article 50 bill|last=|first=|date=1 February 2017|publisher=BBC|accessdate=1 February 2017}}</ref> the bill passed into law as the [[European Union (Notification of Withdrawal) Act 2017]].  Theresa May signed the letter invoking Article 50 on 28 March 2017, which was delivered on 29 March by [[Tim Barrow]], the UK's ambassador to the EU, to [[Donald Tusk]].<ref name="BBC Brexit letter 28 03 2017">{{cite web | title=Article 50: May signs letter that will trigger Brexit | website=BBC News | date=28 March 2017 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-39422353 | accessdate=28 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=eucopresident |number= 847048551792291840|date=29 March 2017 |title=The Article 50 letter. #Brexit|author=Tusk, Donald }}</ref><ref name="Stamp Hunt 2017">{{cite web | last=Stamp | first=Gavin | last2=Hunt | first2=Alex | title=Theresa May officially starts Brexit process | website=BBC News | date=28 March 2017 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/live/uk-politics-39424391 | accessdate=29 March 2017}}</ref>

===Informal discussions===
On 20 July 2016, following her first overseas trip as prime minister, during which she flew to Berlin for talks with German Chancellor [[Angela Merkel]], Theresa May reaffirmed her intention not to trigger Article 50 before 2017, suggesting it would take time for the UK to negotiate a "sensible and orderly departure" from the EU. However, although Merkel said it was right for the UK to "take a moment" before beginning the process, she urged May to provide more clarity on a timetable for negotiations. Shortly before travelling to Berlin, May had also announced that in the wake of the referendum, Britain would relinquish the [[presidency of the Council of the European Union]], which passes between member states every six months on a rotation basis, and that the UK had been scheduled to hold in the second half of 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36841066 |title=Brexit: Theresa May says talks won't start in 2016 |publisher=BBC News  |date=20 July 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Rowena |last=Mason |first2=Philip |last2=Oltermann |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/20/angela-merkel-backs-theresa-mays-plan-not-to-trigger-brexit-this-year |title=Angela Merkel backs Theresa May's plan not to trigger Brexit this year |newspaper=The Guardian |date=20 July 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref>

==Geographical variations within the UK, and implications==
{{multiple image
 | align = right
 | image1 = United Kingdom EU referendum 2016 voting regions results.svg
 | width1 = 250
 | image2 = United Kingdom EU referendum 2016 area results 2-tone.svg
 | width2 = 260
 | footer = Results by country/region (left) and by district/parliamentary constituency (right)<br> 
{{legend|#0069b5|Leave majority}}
{{legend|#ffc010|Remain majority}}
}}

The distribution of Remain and Leave votes varied dramatically across the country.<ref name="Split"/> Remain won every single Scottish district, most [[London boroughs]], Gibraltar and the predominantly Catholic parts of Northern Ireland, as well as many English and Welsh cities. Leave by contrast won almost all other English and Welsh districts and most of the predominantly [[Ulster Protestant]] districts, and won a majority in Wales as a whole as well as every [[Regions of England|English region]] outside London. These results were interpreted by many commentators as revealing a "split" or "divided" country, and exacerbated regional tensions.<ref name="Split"/><ref name="Divided">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jun/23/united-kingdom-two-nations-political-chasm-left|title=The UK is now two nations, staring across a political chasm |author=John Harris|date=23 June 2016|accessdate=8 July 2016|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>

Following the referendum result the all-party Constitution Reform Group announced its intention to publish a draft Act of Union bill outlining a proposed federal constitutional structure for the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|title=Brexit vote paves way for federal union to save UK, says all-party group|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/10/brexit-vote-paves-way-for-federal-union-says-all-party-group|author=Martin Kettle|date=10 July 2016|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=11 July 2016}}</ref> Among its proposals are the establishment of an [[English Parliament]], replacing the [[House of Lords (United Kingdom)|House of Lords]] with a directly elected chamber, and greater devolution for the English regions, following a similar format to that of the [[Greater Manchester Combined Authority]].<ref>{{cite news|first=David W. B. |last=Burnside |url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/opinion/news-analysis/why-a-radical-new-act-of-union-could-resolve-the-uks-political-crisis-34894094.html |title=Why a radical new Act of Union could resolve the UK's political crisis |newspaper=The Belfast Telegraph |date=19 July 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref>

===England===
Of the constituent countries in the United Kingdom, England voted most in favour of leaving the European Union with 53% of voters choosing to leave compared to 47% of voters who chose to remain. Every region apart from [[Greater London]] returned large majority votes in favour of "Leave". The largest regional vote in favour of "Leave" was recorded in the [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]] which saw 59% of voters chose to leave the EU which was closely followed by the [[East Midlands]] which saw 58% of voters opting to leave. The East Midlands also saw the two highest local authority votes in the United Kingdom in favour of leaving the EU which was recorded in the [[Borough of Boston]] in [[Lincolnshire]] in which 75.6% of voters chose to leave which was closely followed by the neighbouring local authority [[South Holland District Council|South Holland]] which saw 73% of voters there opting to leave.<ref name="auto1">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36616747|title=England's most pro and anti-EU boroughs|first1=|last1=|first2=|last=|date=24 June 2016}}</ref>

===Scotland===
[[File:United Kingdom EU referendum 2016 area results (Scotland).svg|thumb|right|200px|All 32 Scottish council areas returned majority votes in favour of "Remain" in Scotland
{{legend|#0069b5|Leave}}
{{legend|#ffc010|Remain}}]]
{{Main|Proposed second Scottish independence referendum}}

Scotland voted 62% to remain in the European Union, with all 32 council areas returning a majority for remaining (albeit with an extremely narrow margin of 122 votes in [[Moray]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/eu_referendum/results |title=EU Referendum Results |work=BBC News |date=1 January 1970 |accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> Scottish First Minister Nicola Sturgeon said it was "clear that the people of Scotland see their future as part of the European Union" and that Scotland had "spoken decisively" with a "strong, unequivocal" vote to remain in the European Union.<ref name="ft2">{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/06a90f8c-39c0-11e6-a780-b48ed7b6126f,Authorised=false.html?siteedition=uk&_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F06a90f8c-39c0-11e6-a780-b48ed7b6126f.html%3Fsiteedition%3Duk&_i_referer=&classification=conditional_standard&iab=barrier-app|title=Scots' backing for Remain raises threat of union's demise|first=Mure|last=Dickie|date=24 June 2016|via=Financial Times}}</ref> The [[Scottish Government]] announced on 24 June 2016 that officials would plan for a "highly likely" [[Proposed second Scottish independence referendum|second referendum]] on [[Scottish independence|independence from the United Kingdom]] and start preparing legislation to that effect.<ref name="nbcnews.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/brexit-referendum/scotland-could-seek-independence-again-after-u-k-brexit-vote-n598166|title='Brexit' Triggers New Bid for Scottish Independence|publisher=[[NBC News]]|last=Jamieson|first=Alastair|date=24 June 2016}}</ref> Former First Minister [[Alex Salmond]] said the vote was a "significant and material change" in Scotland's position within the United Kingdom, and that he was certain his party would implement its manifesto on holding a second referendum.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/24/alex-salmond-second-scottish-independence-referendum-is-certain|title=Nicola Sturgeon prepares for second Scottish independence poll|first=Severin|last=Carrell|work=The Guardian|date=24 June 2016}}</ref> Sturgeon said she will communicate to all EU member states that "Scotland has voted to stay in the EU and I intend to discuss all options for doing so."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/live/2016/jun/23/eu-referendum-result-live-counting-leave-remain-brain-in-europe|title=Nicola Sturgeon says second Scottish referendum 'highly likely' – as it happened|date=24 June 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref> An emergency cabinet meeting on 25 June 2016 agreed that the Scottish Government would "begin immediate discussions with the EU institutions and other member states to explore all the possible options to protect Scotland's place in the EU."<ref name="auto1b">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jun/25/sturgeon-seeks-urgent-brussels-talks-to-protect-scotlands-eu-membership|title=Sturgeon to lobby EU members to support Scotland's bid to remain|first1=Severin|last1=Carrell|first2=Jennifer|last2=Rankin|work=The Guardian|date=25 June 2016}}</ref>

On 26 June, First Minister [[Nicola Sturgeon]] told the BBC that Scotland could attempt to refuse legislative consent for the UK's exit from the European Union,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36633244 |title=Nicola Sturgeon says MSPs at Holyrood could refuse Brexit consent |work=BBC News |date=26 June 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> and on 28 June, established a "standing council" of experts to advise her on how to protect Scotland's relationship with the EU.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36645355 |title=Sturgeon sets up expert group to advise on aftermath of Brexit vote |publisher=BBC News  |date=28 June 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> On the same day she made the following statement: "I want to be clear to parliament that whilst I believe that independence is the best option for Scotland – I don’t think that will come as a surprise to anyone – it is not my starting point in these discussions. My starting point is to protect our relationship with the EU."<ref name="thecourier1">{{cite news |author=Press Association<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Nicola Sturgeon says independence vote would be proposed 'if best or only way to protect EU place'|url=https://www.thecourier.co.uk/fp/news/politics/scottish-politics/215192/nicola-sturgeon-says-independence-vote-proposed-best-way-protect-eu-place/ |newspaper=The Courier |location=Dundee, Scotland |date=28 June 2016 |access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref> Sturgeon met with EU leaders in Brussels the next day to discuss Scotland remaining in the EU. Afterwards, she said the reception had been "sympathetic", in spite of France and Spain objecting to negotiations with Scotland, but conceded that she did not underestimate the challenges.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36656980 |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Brexit: Spain and France oppose Scotland EU talks |date=29 June 2016 |publisher=BBC News  |access-date=29 June 2016 |quote=The French president and Spanish prime minister have both said they are opposed to the EU negotiating potential membership for Scotland.}}</ref>

Also on 28 June, Scottish MEP [[Alyn Smith]] received standing ovations from the [[European Parliament]] for a speech ending ''"Scotland did not let you down, do not let Scotland down."''<ref>{{cite web |author=Sarah Joanne Taylor |title='Scotland's voice will be heard' – Sturgeon vows to fight to maintain EU ties |publisher=[[euronews]] |url=http://www.euronews.com/2016/06/28/scotland-s-voice-will-be-heard-sturgeon-vows-to-fight-to-maintain-eu-ties/ |date=28 June 2016 |accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref> [[Manfred Weber]], the leader of the [[European People's Party Group]] and a key ally of [[Angela Merkel]], said Scotland would be welcome to remain a member of the EU.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ft.com/fastft/2016/06/24/scotland-n-ireland-can-stay-in-eu-says-merkel-ally/|title=Fast FT|first=FT|last=Membership}}</ref> In an earlier ''[[Welt am Sonntag]]'' interview, [[:de:Gunther Krichbaum|Gunther Krichbaum]], chairman of the [[Bundestag]]'s European affairs committee, stated that "the EU will still consist of 28 member states, as I expect a new independence referendum in Scotland, which will then be successful," and urged to "respond quickly to an application for admission from the EU-friendly country."<ref>{{cite news |title=Scotland welcome to join EU, Merkel ally says |agency=[[Reuters]] |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-scotland-germany-idUSKCN0ZC0QT |date=26 June 2016 |accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref>

In a note to the US bank's clients, [[JP Morgan]] Senior Western Europe economist Malcolm Barr wrote: "Our base case is that Scotland will vote for independence and institute a new currency" by 2019.<ref>{{cite news |author=Michael Settle |title=US investment bank JP Morgan says it expects Scotland to vote for independence by end of decade following UK's Brexit decision |newspaper=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] |location=Glasgow |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/politics/14587233.US_investment_bank_JP_Morgan_expects_Scotland_to_vote_for_independence_by_end_of_decade/ |date=29 June 2016 |accessdate=29 June 2016}}</ref>

On 15 July, following her first official talks with Nicola Sturgeon at [[Bute House]], Theresa May said that she was "willing to listen to options" on Scotland's future relationship with the European Union and wanted the Scottish government to be "fully involved" with discussions, but that Scotland had sent a "very clear message" on independence in 2014. Sturgeon said she was "very pleased" that May would listen to the Scottish Government, but that it would be "completely wrong" to block a referendum if it was wanted by the people of Scotland.<ref>{{cite news|first=Libby |last=Brooks |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jul/15/theresa-may-nicola-sturgeon-holyrood-article-50-decision |title=May tells Sturgeon Holyrood will be 'fully engaged' in EU talks |newspaper=The Guardian |date=15 July 2016 |accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36800536 |title=Brexit: PM is 'willing to listen to options' on Scotland |publisher=BBC News  |date=15 July 2016 |accessdate=15 July 2016}}</ref> Two days later, Sturgeon told the BBC that she would consider holding a referendum for 2017 if the UK began the process of exiting the European Union without Scotland's future being secured.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36819182 |title=Sturgeon: Second independence referendum could be next year |publisher=BBC News  |date=17 July 2016 |accessdate=17 July 2016}}</ref> She also suggested it may be possible for Scotland to remain part of the UK while also remaining part of the EU.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2016-07-17/scotland-could-stay-part-of-both-the-eu-and-the-uk/ |title=Scotland 'could stay part of both the EU and the UK' |work=ITV News |publisher=ITV |date=17 July 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> However, on 20 July, this idea was dismissed by Attorney General [[Jeremy Wright]], who told the House of Commons that no part of the UK had a veto over the Article 50 process.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-scotland-politics-36855936 |title=Attorney General: No Scottish veto over Brexit |publisher=BBC News  |date=20 July 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref>

On 28 March 2017, the Scottish parliament voted 69-59 in favour of holding a new referendum on Scottish Independence,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.gov.scot/news/parliament-backs-independence-referendum|title=Parliament backs independence referendum|publisher=Scottish Government|accessdate=17 April 2017}}</ref> and on 31 March, Nicola Sturgeon wrote to PM May requesting permission to hold a second referendum.

