{{see also|United Ireland}}
A referendum on [[United Ireland|Irish unification]] has been advocated by [[Sinn Féin]], the largest nationalist/republican party in Ireland, which is represented both in the [[Northern Ireland Assembly]] and [[Dáil Éireann]] in the [[Republic of Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/world-news/sinn-fein-demands-poll-united-8271274|title=Sinn Fein is demanding a poll on a United Ireland after Brexit|first=David|last=Young|date=24 June 2016|work=Daily Mirror}}</ref> Northern Ireland's deputy First Minister, [[Martin McGuinness]] of Sinn Féin, called for a referendum on the subject following the UK's vote to leave the EU because the majority of the Northern Irish population voted to remain.<ref name="independent.co.uk">"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-northern-ireland-eu-referendum-result-latest-live-border-poll-united-martin-mcguinness-a7099276.html EU referendum result: Sinn Fein's Martin McGuinness calls for border poll on united Ireland after Brexit]". ''The Independent''. 24 June 2016.</ref> The First Minister, [[Arlene Foster]] of the [[Democratic Unionist Party]], said that Northern Ireland's status remained secure and that the vote had strengthened the union within the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/brexit-norths-constitutional-status-secure-says-dup-leader-arlene-foster-406884.html|title=Brexit: North’s constitutional status secure, says DUP leader Arlene Foster|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016|newspaper=Irish Examiner|author=David Young}}</ref> This was echoed by DUP MLA [[Ian Paisley Jr.]], who nevertheless recommended that constituents apply for an [[Irish passport]] to retain EU rights.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/unionist-ian-paisley-jr-mp-constituents-apply-republic-of-ireland-eire-passports-a7102761.html|title=Ian Paisley Jr urges Northern Irish citizens to apply for Republic of Ireland passports|author=Matt Payton|newspaper=Independent|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>

===Wales===
[[File:United Kingdom EU referendum 2016 area results (Wales).svg|thumb|right|200px|Wales along with England voted to leave.
{{legend|#0069b5|Leave}}
{{legend|#ffc010|Remain}}]]
{{main|Welsh independence}}
Although Wales voted to leave the European Union, [[Leanne Wood]], the leader of [[Plaid Cymru]] suggested that the result had "changed everything" and that it was time to begin a debate about independence for Wales. Sources including ''[[The Guardian]]'' have noted that opinion polls tend to put the number in favour of Wales seceding from the United Kingdom at 10%, but Wood suggested in a speech shortly after the referendum that attitudes could change following the result: "The Welsh economy and our constitution face unprecedented challenges. We must explore options that haven’t been properly debated until now."<ref>{{cite news|first=Steven |last=Morris |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/27/its-time-to-put-welsh-independence-on-agenda-leanne-wood |title=It's time to put Welsh independence on agenda – Leanne Wood |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 June 2016 |accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> On 5 July, a YouGov opinion poll commissioned by [[ITV Wales]] indicated that 35% would vote in favour of Welsh independence in the event that it meant Wales could stay in the European Union, but Professor [[Roger Scully]], of [[Cardiff University]]'s Wales Governance Centre said the poll indicated a "clear majority" against Wales ceasing to be part of the UK: “The overall message appears to be that while Brexit might reopen the discussion on Welsh independence there is little sign that the Leave vote in the EU referendum has yet inclined growing numbers of people to vote Leave in a referendum on Welsh independence from the UK."<ref>{{cite news|last=Shipton |first=Martin |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/third-voters-would-back-independence-11567766 |title=A third of voters would back independence for Wales – if the country could stay in the EU as the rest of the UK left |newspaper=Western Mail |date=5 July 2016 |accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref>

===Greater London===
[[File:United Kingdom EU referendum 2016 area results (Greater London).svg|thumb|right|200px|Voting on the referendum in Greater London
{{legend|#0069b5|Leave}}
{{legend|#ffc010|Remain}}]]
{{Main|London independence}}
[[Greater London]] voted to remain in the EU, and Scottish First Minister Nicola Sturgeon said she had spoken to London Mayor [[Sadiq Khan]] about the possibility of remaining in the EU and said he shared that objective for London. A petition calling on Khan to [[London secessionism|declare London independent]] from the UK received tens of thousands of signatures.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36620401|title=Petition for London independence signed by thousands after Brexit vote|work=BBC News|date=24 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/londependence-petition-calls-for-london-to-join-the-eu-on-its-own-a7101006.html|title='Londependence' petition calls for London to join the EU on its own|date=24 June 2016}}</ref> The BBC reported the petition as [[tongue-in-cheek]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-trending-36620558 |title=After Brexit vote, a tongue-in-cheek call for independence for London |work=BBC |date=24 July 2016}}</ref> Supporters of London's independence argued that London's demographic, culture and values are different from the rest of England, and that it should become a [[city state]] similar to Singapore, while remaining an EU member state.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2016/06/24/londoners-want-their-own-independence-after-brexit-result/|title=Londoners want their own independence after Brexit result|work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://metro.co.uk/2016/06/24/70000-sign-petition-for-london-to-become-independent-and-rejoin-the-eu-5965541/|title=70,000 sign petition for London to become independent and rejoin the EU|author=Nicole Morley|work=Metro|date=24 June 2016}}</ref> [[Spencer Livermore, Baron Livermore]], said that London's independence "should be a goal," arguing that a London city-state would have twice the GDP of Singapore.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/eu-referendum-london-independence_uk_576d4c57e4b0d257114993a2|title=London Independence Goes Beyond A Twitter Joke With Politicians Seriously Discussing It|date=24 June 2016}}</ref> Khan said that complete independence was unrealistic, but demanded devolving more powers and autonomy for London.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sadiq Khan: Now London must 'take back control', 28 June 2016|url=https://www.london.gov.uk/press-releases/mayoral/mayor-addresses-top-business-leaders|publisher=london.gov.uk|accessdate=13 July 2016}}</ref>

===Gibraltar===

{{main|Gibraltar after Brexit}}

Spain's foreign minister [[José García-Margallo y Marfil|José Manuel García-Margallo]] said "It's a complete change of outlook that opens up new possibilities on Gibraltar not seen for a very long time. I hope the formula of co-sovereignty – to be clear, the Spanish flag on the Rock – is much closer than before."<ref name="uk.reuters.com">{{cite news |title=Spain to seek co-sovereignty on Gibraltar after Brexit |url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-britain-eu-gibraltar-idUKKCN0ZA169 |agency=Reuters |date= 24 June 2016}}</ref> Gibraltar's Chief Minister [[Fabian Picardo]] however immediately dismissed García-Margallo's remarks, stating that "there will be no talks, or even talks about talks, about the sovereignty of Gibraltar", and asked Gibraltar's citizens "to ignore these noises".<ref>{{cite web |title=Gibraltar stands defiant against Spain after Brexit vote |work=[[The Local]] |url=http://www.thelocal.es/20160624/gibraltar-defiant-against-spain-after-brexit |date=24 June 2016 |accessdate=24 June 2016}}</ref> This is while he was in talks with Nicola Sturgeon, the First Minister of Scotland, to keep Gibraltar in the EU, while remaining British too. He said that "I can imagine a situation where some parts of what is today the member state United Kingdom are stripped out and others remain." Nicola Sturgeon said on the same day that talks were under way with Gibraltar to build a "common cause" on EU membership.<ref name="Gatehouse Gibraltar 2016">{{cite web | last=Gatehouse | first=Gabriel | title=Brexit: Gibraltar in talks with Scotland to stay in EU | publisher=BBC News | date=27 June 2016 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36639770 | accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="The Independent Gibraltar 2016">{{cite news | title=Scotland is talking to Gibraltar to see if it can stay in the EU after Brexit | website=The Independent | date=27 June 2016 | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/brexit-gibraltar-scotland-taks-to-stay-in-eu-referendum-result-latest-a7106306.html | accessdate=27 June 2016}}</ref>

==Republic of Ireland==
The Republic of Ireland, which shares a land border with the United Kingdom, joined the then European Communities alongside its neighbour on 1 January 1973, and as of 2016, its trade with the UK was worth £840m (€1bn) a week, while as many as 380,000 Irish citizens were employed in the UK. Britain was also a significant contributor towards the 2010 [[Economic Adjustment Programme for Ireland|bailout package]] that was put together in the wake of the [[Post-2008 Irish banking crisis|banking crisis]] of the late 2000s. Concerned by the possibility of a UK vote to leave the EU, in 2015, [[Enda Kenny]], the [[Taoiseach]] of Ireland, established an office to put together a contingency plan in the event of a Brexit vote.<ref name="Bloomberg Ireland"/><ref name="BBC Ireland">{{cite news|last=Harrison |first=Shane |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-36839998 |title=Brexit: Irish concerns over implications of UK vote |publisher=BBC News  |date=20 July 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref>

On 18 July 2016, ''[[Bloomberg News]]'' reported that the UK's vote to leave the EU was having a negative impact on the Republic of Ireland, a country with close economic and cultural ties to the UK. Share prices in Ireland fell after the result, while exporters warned that a weaker UK currency would drive down wages and economic growth in a country still recovering from the effects of the banking crisis. [[John Bruton]], who served as Taoiseach from 1994 to 1997, and later an EU ambassador to the United States, described Britain's vote to leave the European Union as "the most serious, difficult issue facing the country for 50 years".<ref name="Bloomberg Ireland">{{cite news|first=Dara |last=Doyle |first2=Marc |last2=Champion |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-17/ireland-hits-brexit-alarm-in-biggest-foreign-crisis-in-50-years |title=Ireland Hits Brexit Alarm in Biggest Foreign Crisis in 50 Years |work=Bloomberg News |publisher=Bloomberg |date=18 July 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> Nick Ashmore, head of the [[Strategic Banking Corporation of Ireland]] argued the uncertainty caused by the result had made attracting new business lenders into Ireland more difficult.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/business/brexit/brexit-decision-makes-it-harder-to-attract-new-business-lenders-to-ireland-sbci-boss-34902243.html |title=Brexit decision makes it harder to attract new business lenders to Ireland – SBCI boss |newspaper=The Irish Independent |date=21 July 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> However, John McGrane, director general of the British Irish Chamber of Commerce, said the organisation had been inundated with enquiries from UK firms wishing to explore the feasibility of basing themselves in a country "with the same language and legal system and with a commitment to staying in the EU".<ref name="BBC Ireland"/>

On 21 July, following talks in Dublin, Kenny and French President [[Francois Hollande]] issued a joint statement saying they "looked forward to the notification as soon as possible by the new British government of the UK's intention to withdraw from the Union" because it would "permit orderly negotiations to begin".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-36850619 |title=Ireland and France call for EU Brexit process to start 'as soon as possible' |publisher=BBC News  |date=21 July 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref> Hollande also suggested Ireland should secure a "special situation" in discussions with European leaders during the UK's European withdrawal negotiations.<ref>{{cite news|first=Juno |last=McEnroe |url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/brexit-represents-special-situation-for-ireland-says-hollande-745917.html |title=Brexit represents 'special situation for Ireland', says Hollande |newspaper=The Irish Examiner |publisher=Landmark Media Investments |date=21 July 2016 |accessdate=21 July 2016}}</ref>

==Racist abuse and hate crimes==
More than a hundred racist abuse and hate crimes were reported in the immediate aftermath of the referendum with many citing the plan to leave the European Union, with police saying there had been a five-fold increase since the vote.<ref name="brexitwaveofracialabuse">{{cite news|last1=Agerholm|first1=Harriet|title=Brexit: Wave of racial abuse and hate crime reported after EU referendum|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/brexit-eu-referendum-racial-racism-abuse-hate-crime-reported-latest-leave-immigration-a7104191.html|accessdate=26 June 2016|work=The Independent|date=26 June 2016}}</ref> On 24 June, a school in [[Cambridgeshire]] was vandalised with a sign reading "Leave the EU. No more Polish vermin."<ref name="policeproberaicstsignsstandard">{{cite news|last1=Micklewaithte|first1=Jamie|title=Police probe 'racist signs distributed after Brexit vote in EU referendum'|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/crime/police-probe-racist-signs-distributed-after-brexit-vote-in-eu-referendum-a3281021.html|accessdate=26 June 2016|work=London Evening Standard|date=26 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/jun/30/police-report-fivefold-increase-race-hate-crimes-since-brexit-result|title=Police log fivefold rise in race-hate complaints since Brexit result|author=Nazia Parveen |author2=Harriet Sherwood|date=30 June 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016|newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> Following the referendum result, similar signs were distributed outside homes and schools in [[Huntingdon]], with some left on the cars of Polish residents collecting their children from school.<ref name="auto4">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-cambridgeshire-36633388|title=Anti-Polish cards in Huntingdon after EU referendum|publisher=BBC News|access-date=26 June 2016}}</ref> On 26 June, the London office of the [[Polish Social and Cultural Association]] was vandalised with racist graffiti.<ref name="policeproberacistgraffiti">{{cite news|last1=Micklewaithte|first1=Jamie|title=Police probe racist graffiti smeared on Polish centre after Brexit vote|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/police-probe-racist-graffiti-smeared-on-polish-centre-after-brexit-vote-a3281081.html|accessdate=26 June 2016|work=London Evening Standard|date=26 June 2016}}</ref> Both incidents were investigated by the police.<ref name="policeproberaicstsignsstandard"/><ref name="policeproberacistgraffiti"/>  Other instances of racism occurred as perceived foreigners were targeted in supermarkets, on buses and on street corners, and told to leave the country immediately.<ref name="guardianracistincidents">{{cite news|last1=Lyons|first1=Kate|title=Racist incidents feared to be linked to Brexit result|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/26/racist-incidents-feared-to-be-linked-to-brexit-result-reported-in-england-and-wales|accessdate=26 June 2016|work=The Guardian|date=26 June 2016}}</ref> The hate crimes were widely condemned by politicians, the UN and religious groups.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sherwood |first=Harriet|date=27 June 2016 |title=Cameron condemns xenophobic and racist abuse after Brexit vote |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2016/jun/27/sadiq-khan-muslim-council-britain-warning-of-post-brexit-racism?subid=17310058&CMP=EMCNEWEML6619I2 |newspaper=The Guardian |location=London, UK |access-date=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Rob Merrick |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-brexiter-daniel-hannan-eu-referendum-campaign-caused-spike-hate-crime-racism-leave-campaign-a7237216.html |title=Tory Leave campaigner denies Brexit caused hate crime increase |work=The Independent |date=11 September 2016 |accessdate=24 June 2017}}</ref> MEP [[Daniel Hannan]] disputed both the accuracy of reporting and connection to the referendum,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://corporate.sky.com/media-centre/media-packs/2016/murnaghan-interview-with-daniel-hannan,-mep,-tory-vote-leave-campaigner,-110916 |title=Murnaghan Interview with Daniel Hannan, MEP, Tory Vote Leave campaigner |publisher=[[Sky News]] |date=11 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/28/we-leavers-are-not-racists-bigots-or-hooligans--no-matter-what-t/ |title=We Leavers are not racists, bigots, or hooligans – no matter what the bitter broadcasters say |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=28 June 2016}}</ref> in turn receiving criticism for rejecting evidence.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-brexiter-daniel-hannan-eu-referendum-campaign-caused-spike-hate-crime-racism-leave-campaign-a7237216.html |title=Tory Leave campaigner denies Brexit caused hate crime increase |work=[[The Independent]] |date=11 September 2016}}</ref>

On 8 July 2016, figures released by the [[National Police Chiefs' Council]] indicated there were 3,076 reported hate crimes and incidents across England, Wales and Northern Ireland between 16–30 June, compared to 2,161 for the same period in 2015, a 42% increase; the number of incidents peaked on 25 June, when there were 289 reported cases. Assistant Chief Constable Mark Hamilton, the council's lead on hate crime, described the "sharp rise" as unacceptable.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-36746763 |title='Sharp rise' in reported hate crime |publisher=BBC News  |date=8 July 2016 |accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Caroline |last=Mortimer |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/brexit-hate-crime-racism-stats-spike-police-england-wales-eu-referendum-a7126706.html |title=Hate crimes surge by 42% in England and Wales since Brexit result |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=8 July 2016 |accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> The figures were reported to have shown the greatest increase in areas that voted strongly to leave.<ref>{{cite news |author=Jon Stone |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/crime/brexit-hate-crime-racism-immigration-eu-referendum-result-what-it-means-eurospectic-areas-a7165056.html |title=Brexit: Surge in anti-immigrant hate crime in areas that voted to leave EU |work=The Independent |date= |accessdate=24 June 2017}}</ref>

==Post-referendum campaigning==

===Petition for a new referendum===
{{see also|United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016#Petition for a new referendum}}
Within hours of the result's announcement, a petition, calling for a second referendum to be held in the event that a result was secured with less than 60% of the vote and on a turnout of less than 75%, attracted tens of thousands of new signatures. The petition had been initiated by William Oliver Healey of the [[English Democrats]] on 24 May 2016, when the Remain faction had been leading in the polls, and had received 22 signatures prior to the referendum result being declared.<ref name=investigation/><ref name=Healey>{{cite news|first=Chris |last=York |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/william-oliver-healey-referendum-petition_uk_576f8b28e4b0232d331e1b39 |title=Second EU Referendum Petition Started By Leave Voter William Oliver Healey |work=The Huffington Post |publisher=Verizon |date=26 June 2016 |accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=BBC-Coleman/> On 26 June, Healey said that the petition had actually been started to favour an exit from the EU and that he was a strong supporter of the Vote Leave and Grassroots Out campaigns. Healey also said that the petition had been "hijacked by the remain campaign".<ref>
{{cite web |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/brexit-referendum/brexit-redux-petition-second-eu-vote-hits-3-million-signatures-n599156 |title=Brexit Redux? Petition for Second EU Vote Hits 3 Million Signatures |last=Marker |first=Christina |date=26 June 2016 |publisher=NBC News |access-date=26 June 2016 |quote=In an ironic twist, it emerged Sunday that the petition's creator was in fact in favor of so-called Brexit. In a message posted to Facebook, William Oliver Healey sought to distance himself from the petition, saying it had been hijacked by those in favor of remaining in the EU.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/27/petition-calling-for-second-eu-referendum-was-created-by-a-leave/ |title=Petition calling for second EU referendum was created by a Leave voter – and he’s not happy that it’s been 'hijacked' by Remain |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=27 June 2016}}</ref> English Democrats chairman [[Robin Tilbrook]] suggested those who had signed the petition were experiencing "sour grapes" about the result of the referendum.<ref name="auto5">{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/06/26/europe/uk-second-referendum-petition/ |title=Brexit: Petition calling for second EU vote was created by Leave backer |first=Tim |last=Hume |publisher=CNN |access-date=26 June 2016}}</ref>

By late July it had attracted over 4 million signatures, about one quarter of the total number of remain votes in the referendum and over forty times the 100,000 needed for any petition to be considered for debate in Parliament. As many as a thousand signatures per minute were being added during the day after the referendum vote, causing the website to crash on several occasions.<ref>{{cite news|first=Christopher |last=Hooton |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/brexit-petition-for-second-eu-referendum-so-popular-the-government-sites-crashing-a7099996.html |title=Brexit: Petition for second EU referendum so popular the government site's crashing |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=24 June 2016 |accessdate=24 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Adam |last=Boult |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/28/petition-for-second-eu-referendum-hits-4-million-as-hundreds-att/ |title=Petition for second EU referendum attracts thousands of signatures |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=26 June 2016 |accessdate=30 June 2016}}</ref> Some of the signatories had abstained from voting or had voted leave but regretted their decision, in what the media dubbed "bregret",<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-anger-bregret-leave-voters-protest-vote-thought-uk-stay-in-eu-remain-win-a7102516.html|title=Anger over 'Bregret' as Leave voters say they thought UK would stay in EU|work=The Independent|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/25/eu-referendum-brexit-prime-minister-tory-mps-boris-johnson-leade/|title=EU referendum: Battle to be Brexit Prime Minister heats up as Tory MPs question Boris Johnson's leadership credentials|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref> or "regrexit" at the result.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/25/politics/uk-referendum-regrexit/|title=Brexit: Do you #Regrexit? UK voters voice doubt over referendum choice|publisher=CNN|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jun/25/48-britain-regrexit-voted-remaon|title=For the 48%, this was a day of despair|work=The Guardian|date=25 June 2016|accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref>

No previous government petition had attracted as many signatures, but it was reported that the House of Commons Petitions Committee were investigating allegations of fraud. Chair of that committee, [[Helen Jones]], said that the allegations were being taken seriously, and any signatures found to be fraudulent would be removed from the petition: "People adding fraudulent signatures to this petition should know that they undermine the cause they pretend to support."<ref name=investigation>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36634407 |title=Second EU referendum petition investigated for fraud |publisher=BBC News  |date=26 June 2016 |accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> By the afternoon of 26 June the House of Commons' petitions committee said that it had removed "about 77,000 signatures which were added fraudulently" and that it would continue to monitor the petition for "suspicious activity"; almost 40,000 signatures seemed to have come from the [[Vatican City]], which has a population of under 1,000.<ref name=telegraphsecond/> Hackers from [[4chan]] claimed that they had added the signatures with the use of [[automated bot]]s,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-36640459 |title=EU referendum petition hijacked by bots |publisher=BBC News  |date=27 June 2016 |accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref> and that it was done as a prank.<ref name=telegraphsecond>{{cite news |last=Heighton |first=Luke |date=26 June 2016 |title=Second referendum petition: At least 77,000 'fake' signatures removed hours after inquiry launched |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/26/concern-as-online-call-for-second-brexit-vote-gains-more-than-39/ |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London, UK |access-date=26 June 2016 }}</ref>

{{Quote_box |width=40% |bgcolor=#E0E0F8 |align=right|source=Email to petition signatories from Foreign and Commonwealth Office, 8 July 2016|quote=As the Prime Minister made clear in his statement to the House of Commons on 27 June, the referendum was one of the biggest democratic exercises in British history with over 33 million people having their say. The Prime Minister and Government have been clear that this was a once in a generation vote and, as the Prime Minister has said, the decision must be respected. We must now prepare for the process to exit the EU and the Government is committed to ensuring the best possible outcome for the British people in the negotiations.<ref>{{cite news|first=Harry |last=Cockburn |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-government-rejects-eu-referendum-petition-latest-a7128306.html |title=Brexit: Government rejects petition signed by 4.1 million calling for second EU referendum |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=9 July 2016 |accessdate=9 July 2016}}</ref>}}

On 8 July, the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]] sent an email to all signatories of the petition setting out the government's position. It rejected calls for a second referendum: "Prime Minister and Government have been clear that this was a once in a generation vote and, as the Prime Minister has said, the decision must be respected."<ref>{{cite news|first=Nicola |last=Slawson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/09/government-dashes-hopes-of-second-eu-referendum-in-e-petition-response |title=Government dashes hopes of second EU referendum in e-petition response |newspaper=The Guardian |date=9 July 2016 |accessdate=9 July 2016}}</ref> On 12 July the Committee scheduled a debate on the petition for 5 September because of the "huge number" of people who had signed it, but stressed that this did not mean it was backing calls for a second referendum.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36777494 |title=Brexit: Debate on second EU referendum after millions sign petition |publisher=BBC News  |date=12 July 2016 |accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> The debate, held in [[Westminster Hall]], the House of Commons' second chamber, does not have the power to change the law; a spokesman for the Committee said that the debate would not pave the way for Parliament to decide on holding a second referendum.<ref>{{cite news|first=Hatty |last=Collier |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/second-eu-referendum-petition-will-be-debated-in-parliament-a3294101.html |title=Brexit: Second EU referendum petition to be debated by MPs |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=12 July 2016 |accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2016-07-12/mps-to-debate-second-referendum-after-record-breaking-petition/ |title=MPs to debate second referendum after record-breaking petition |work=ITV News |publisher=ITV |date=12 July 2016 |accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> The petition closed on 26 November 2016, having received 4,150,259 signatures.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://petition.parliament.uk/petitions/131215|title=EU Referendum Rules triggering a 2nd EU Referendum|publisher=petition.parliament.uk|accessdate=27 November 2016}}</ref>

===Backing for a new referendum===
The [[Trades Union Congress|TUC]] fears that any Brexit deal the government might make could harm workers' interests and lead to workers in many industries losing their jobs.  [[Frances O'Grady]] of the TUC said that unless the government provides a deal that is good for working people, the TUC will strongly support calls for a second referendum.  O'Grady said, "I want to serve notice to the prime minister today that if we don't get the deal that working people need, then the TUC will be throwing our full weight behind a campaign for a popular vote so that people get a say on whether that deal is good enough or not,"<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-45464115 Brexit: TUC issues new EU referendum warning to May] ''[[BBC]]''</ref>

===Debate over legitimacy of a second referendum===

The petition initiated a debate over the legitimacy of holding a second referendum. BBC political correspondent [[Iain Watson]] argued that since the petition requests a piece of retrospective legislation, it is unlikely to be enacted,<ref name=investigation/> while David Cameron had previously ruled out holding a second referendum, calling it "a once-in-a-lifetime event".<ref>{{cite news|first=Nicholas |last=Winning |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/british-prime-minister-david-cameron-rules-out-another-vote-on-whether-to-leave-eu-1463492823 |title=British Prime Minister Cameron Rules Out Another Vote on Leaving EU |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=17 May 2016 |accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew |last=Whitaker |url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/uk/david-cameron-rules-out-second-eu-referendum-1-4035895 |title=David Cameron rules out second EU referendum |newspaper=The Scotsman |publisher=Johnston Press |date=22 February 2016 |accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> However, [[Jolyon Maugham]] [[Queen's Counsel|QC]], a barrister specialising in tax law, argued that a second referendum on EU membership could be triggered by one of two scenarios: following a [[snap general election]] won by one or more parties standing on a remain platform, or as a result of parliament deciding that circumstances had changed significantly enough to require a fresh mandate. Maugham cited several instances in which a country's electorate have been asked to reconsider the outcome of a referendum relating to the EU, among them the two [[Treaty of Lisbon]] referendums held in Ireland, in [[Twenty-eighth Amendment of the Constitution Bill 2008|2008]] and [[Twenty-eighth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|2009]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Jolyon |last=Maugham |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/brexit-petition-second-eu-referendum-how-to-get-new-vote-on-uk-membership-a7102646.html |title=How to deliver a second EU referendum |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=25 June 2016 |accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref>

Historian [[Vernon Bogdanor]] said that a second referendum would be "highly unlikely", and suggested governments would be cautious about holding referendums in future,<ref name="Telegraph second referendum"/> but argued it could happen if the EU rethought some of its policies, such as those regarding the [[Freedom of movement for workers in the European Union|free movement of workers]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Vernon |last=Bogdanor |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jul/19/second-referendum-britain-eu-leaders-listen |title=There could still be a second referendum in Britain – if EU leaders listen |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 July 2016 |accessdate=19 July 2016}}</ref> Political scientist [[John Curtice]] agreed that a change of circumstances could result in another referendum, but said the petition would have little effect.<ref name="Telegraph second referendum">{{cite news|first=Camilla |last=Turner |first2=Michael |last2=Wilkinson |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/06/25/could-britain-actually-have-a-second-referendum-on-brexit/ |title=As three million people sign a petition for a second EU referendum we ask – could it actually happen? |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=26 June 2016 |accessdate=26 June 2016}}</ref> BBC legal correspondent [[Clive Coleman]] argued that a second referendum was "constitutionally possible [but] politically unthinkable. It would take something akin to a revolution and full-blown constitutional crisis for it to happen".<ref name=BBC-Coleman>{{cite news|first=Clive |last=Coleman |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-uk-leaves-the-eu-36671629 |title=Can the law stop Brexit? |publisher=BBC News  |date=30 June 2016 |accessdate=2 July 2016}}</ref> Conservative MP [[Dominic Grieve]], a former [[Attorney General (England and Wales)|Attorney General for England and Wales]] said that although the government should respect the result of the referendum, "it is of course possible that it will become apparent with the passage of time that public opinion has shifted on the matter. If so a second referendum may be justified."<ref name=Independent-Grieve>{{cite news|first=Jon |last=Stone |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/dominic-grieve-brexit-second-eu-referendum-legal-former-attorney-general-says-7119491.html |title=Second EU referendum would be possible, former attorney general says |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=4 July 2016 |accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref> Barristers Belinda McRae and Andrew Lodder argued the referendum "is wrongly being treated as a majority vote for the terms of exit that Britain can negotiate [with] the EU" when the public were not asked about the terms of exiting the EU, so a second referendum would be needed on that issue.<ref>{{cite news|last=McRae |first=Belinda |last2=Lodder |first2=Andrew |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/staggers/2016/07/theres-democratic-case-second-referendum-how-it-can-be-done |title=There's a democratic case for a second referendum – this is how it can be done |work=New Statesman |publisher=Progressive Media International |date=6 July 2016 |accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref> [[Richard Dawkins]] argued that if a second referendum upheld the result of the first, it would "unite the country behind Brexit".<ref>{{cite news|last=Dawkins |first=Richard |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/politics/uk/2016/07/second-referendum-only-way-get-britain-back-brexit |title=A second referendum is the only way to get Britain to back Brexit |work=New Statesman |publisher=Progressive Media International |date=16 July 2016 |accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> However, political scientist Liubomir K. Topaloff argued that a second referendum would "surely destroy the EU" because the resulting anger of Leave supporters in the UK would spread anti-EU sentiment in other countries.<ref>{{cite news|first=Liubomir K. |last=Topaloff |url=http://fortune.com/2016/07/03/second-brexit-referendum-eu/ |title=How a Second Brexit Referendum Would Kill the EU |work=Fortune |date=3 July 2016 |accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref>

On 26 June, former prime minister [[Tony Blair]] said the option of holding a second referendum should not be ruled out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2016-06-26/tony-blair-dont-rule-out-a-second-eu-referendum/|title=Tony Blair: 'Don't rule out a second EU referendum'|work=ITV News |publisher=ITV |date=26 June 2016 |accessdate=3 July 2016}}</ref> A week later he suggested the will of the people could change, and that Parliament should reflect that.<ref>{{cite news|first=Ashley |last=Cowburn |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-tony-blair-second-eu-referendum-chilcot-report-latest-news-a7116776.html |title=Tony Blair says the UK 'should keep its options open' over Brexit |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=3 July 2016 |accessdate=3 July 2016}}</ref> [[Alastair Campbell]], the [[Downing Street Director of Communications]] under Blair called for a second referendum setting out "the terms on which we leave. And the terms on which we could remain".<ref>{{cite news|first=Roy |last=Greenslade |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2016/jul/15/the-new-european-lands-alastair-campbell-brexit-scoop |title=Alastair Campbell calls for a second EU referendum |newspaper=The Guardian |date=15 July 2016 |accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> Labour MP [[David Lammy]] commented that, as the referendum was advisory, Parliament should vote on whether to leave the EU.<ref>{{cite news|first=Will |last=Worley |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/brexit-result-latest-david-lammy-mp-eu-referendum-result-parliament-twitter-statement-stop-this-a7102931.html |title=David Lammy MP urges Parliament to ignore EU referendum result: 'We can stop this madness' |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=25 June 2016 |accessdate=25 June 2016}}</ref> On 1 July, Shadow chancellor [[John McDonnell (politician)|John McDonnell]] outlined Labour's vision for leaving the EU, saying that Britain had to respect the decision that was made in the referendum.<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-36680463 EU referendum result must be respected, says John McDonnell] BBC News, 1 July 2016</ref>

Following the first post-referendum meeting of the Cabinet on 27 June, a spokesman for the Prime Minister said that the possibility of a second referendum was "not remotely on the cards. There was a decisive result [in the EU referendum]. The focus of the Cabinet discussion was how we get on and deliver that."<ref name="Cooper"/> Theresa May also ruled out the possibility at the launch of her campaign to succeed Cameron.<ref>{{cite news|first=Jon |last=Stone |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/theresa-may-rules-our-early-general-election-or-second-eu-referendum-if-she-becomes-conservative-a7110656.html |title=Theresa May rules out early general election or second EU referendum if she becomes Conservative leader |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=30 June 2016 |accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> On 28 June, Health Secretary [[Jeremy Hunt (politician)|Jeremy Hunt]] raised the possibility of a second referendum, but said that it would be about the terms of the UK's exit from the European Union rather than on the issue of EU membership.<ref>{{cite news|first=Lizzie |last=Dearden |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-hunt-running-conservative-party-leader-second-eu-referendum-brexit-vote-a7106836.html |title=Jeremy Hunt raises prospect of second EU vote while announcing he may run as Conservative Party leader |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=28 June 2016 |accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref> Labour MP [[Geraint Davies (Labour politician)|Geraint Davies]] also suggested that a second referendum would focus on the terms of an exit plan, with a default of remaining in the EU if it were rejected. Citing a poll published in the week after the referendum that indicated as many as 1.1&nbsp;million people who voted to leave the EU regretted their decision, he tabled an [[early day motion]] calling for an exit package referendum.<ref>{{cite news|first=Geraint |last=Davies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2016/jun/30/second-eu-referendum-pull-us-out-of-fire-make-happen |title=A second EU referendum could pull us out of the fire. Let's make it happen |newspaper=The Guardian |date=30 June 2016 |accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref>

On 26 June it was reported that Conservative grandee [[Michael Heseltine]] was suggesting that a second referendum should take place after Brexit negotiations, pointing to the overwhelming majority in the House of Commons against leaving the EU.<ref>{{cite web|author=Anushka Asthana |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jun/26/fightback-against-brexit-on-cards-remain-eu-referendum-heseltine |title=Parliamentary fightback against Brexit on cards |work=The Guardian |accessdate=1 July 2016}}</ref> On 13 July, Labour leadership candidate [[Owen Smith (politician)|Owen Smith]] said that he would offer a second referendum on the terms of EU withdrawal if elected to lead the party.<ref>{{cite news|first=Anushka |last=Asthana |first2=Heather |last2=Stewart |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/13/owen-smith-to-offer-referendum-on-brexit-deal-if-elected-labour-leader |title=Owen Smith to offer referendum on Brexit deal if elected Labour leader |newspaper=The Guardian |date=13 July 2016 |accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref>

The outcome of the referendum was debated by the [[Church of England]]'s [[General Synod of the Church of England|General Synod]] on 8 July, where [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] [[Justin Welby]] ruled out supporting a second referendum.<ref>{{cite news|first=Harry |last=Farley |url=http://www.christiantoday.com/article/general.synod.church.of.england.opts.to.recognise.eu.referendum.result.despite.opposition/90175.htm |title=General Synod: Church of England opts to 'recognise' EU referendum result despite opposition |work=Christian Today |publisher=Christian Today Limited |date=8 July 2016 |accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> The idea of a second referendum was also rejected by Plaid Cymru leader Leanne Wood, who favoured a general election following negotiations instead.<ref>{{cite news|last=Shipton |first=Martin |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/politics/leanne-wood-says-voters-must-11564187 |title=Leanne Wood says voters 'must be respected' – and criticises calls for a second EU referendum |newspaper=Western Mail |date=4 July 2016 |accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> [[Sammy Wilson (politician)|Sammy Wilson]], a [[Democratic Unionist Party]] MP likened those calling for a second referendum to fascists, saying "They don't wish to have the democratic wishes of the people honoured... They wish to have only their views."<ref>{{cite news|first=Claire |last=Williamson |url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/brexit-dup-mp-sammy-wilson-likens-those-calling-second-eu-vote-to-fascists-34855073.html |title=Brexit: DUP MP Sammy Wilson likens those calling second EU vote to 'fascists' |newspaper=The Belfast Telegraph |date=4 July 2016 |accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>

On 8 July 2016, an ORB poll indicated 40% support for a referendum on the terms of withdrawal from the EU.<ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew |last=Grice |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/brexit-second-referendum-poll-vote-leave-voters-regret-four-out-of-ten-remain-europe-a7127731.html |title=Four out of 10 people want a second EU referendum before Brexit, poll finds |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=8 July 2016 |accessdate=9 July 2016}}</ref> On 16 July 2016, a ComRes poll indicated 57% opposed to a second referendum, with 29% in favour.<ref>{{cite news|first=John |last=Rentoul |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/poll-second-eu-referendum-brexit-theresa-may-general-election-voters-a7140721.html |title=Poll: Voters do not want second EU referendum and say Theresa May should continue without general election |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=16 July 2016 |accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref> On 27 July 2018, a YouGov poll indicated a slim majority in favour of a second referendum.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://yougov.co.uk/news/2018/07/27/first-time-more-people-support-second-referendum/|title=For the first time, more people support a second referendum|first=Smith |last=Matthew |date=27 July 2018|work= [[YouGov]]|accessdate=24 August 2018}}</ref>

===Pro-EU activities===
[[File:London Brexit pro-EU protest March 25 2017 25.jpg|thumb|A Pro-EU march in London, in March 2017]]
Pro-EU demonstrations took place in the days following the referendum result. On 24 June, protesters gathered in cities across the UK, including London, Edinburgh and Glasgow. At one demonstration in London hundreds of protesters marched on the headquarters of [[News UK]] to protest against "anti-immigration politics".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.itv.com/news/2016-06-25/hundreds-march-in-protest-at-anti-immigration-tone-of-brexit-campaign/ |title=Hundreds march in protest at 'anti-immigration' tone of Brexit campaign |work=ITV News |publisher=ITV |date=25 June 2016 |accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref> Protesters on bicycles angry at the result attempted to block Boris Johnson's car as he was leaving his home on the morning of 24 June, while campaigners aged 18–25, as well as some teenagers under the [[age of majority]], staged a protest outside Parliament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rt.com/uk/348294-fk-brexit-rally-remain/ |title="F**k Brexit rally": Pro-remain campaigners call for mass protest at Houses of Parliament |publisher=RT |date=24 June 2016 |accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Hatty |last=Collier |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/politics/brexit-teenagers-stage-protest-outside-parliament-at-eu-referendum-result-a3280626.html |title=Brexit: Teenagers stage protest outside parliament at EU referendum result |newspaper=London Evening Standard |date=24 June 2016 |accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref>

On 28 June, up to 50,000 people attended Stand Together, a pro-EU demonstration organised for London's [[Trafalgar Square]], despite the event having been officially cancelled amid safety concerns. The organiser had announced the rally on social media, with a view to bringing "20 friends together", but urged people not to attend as the number of people expressing interest reached 50,000. The meeting was addressed by Liberal Democrat leader Tim Farron before protesters made their way to [[Whitehall]]. A similar event in Cardiff was addressed by speakers including [[Plaid Cymru]] leader [[Leanne Wood]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Ashley |last=Cowburn |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/eu-referendum-rally-brexit-cancelled-nigel-farage-boris-johnson-leave-remain-a7108616.html |title=Protesters chant 'down with Boris' in anti-Brexit rally outside Parliament |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=29 June 2016 |accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref> On 2 July, around 50,000 demonstrators marched in London to show support for the EU and to demand that Britain continues to co-operate with other European states.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/02/march-for-europe-eu-referendum-london-protest|title='We are the 48%': tens of thousands march in London for Europe |newspaper=The Observer|author=Ed Vulliamy|date=2 July 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-36692990 |title=Thousands at 'March for Europe' Brexit protest |publisher=BBC News  |date=2 July 2016 |accessdate=5 July 2016}}</ref> A similar event was held in Edinburgh outside the [[Scottish Parliament building]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stv.tv/news/east-central/1359115-thousands-attend-pro-eu-demo-outside-scottish-parliament/|title=Thousands attend pro-EU demo outside Scottish Parliament|date=29 June 2016|accessdate=4 July 2016|work=STV News |publisher=STV}}</ref>

On 8 July 2016, and in response to the referendum result, ''[[The New European]]'', was launched with an initial print run of 200,000. This is a national weekly newspaper aimed at people who voted to remain in the EU, which its editor felt had not been represented by the traditional media, and remains in print as of December 2017.<ref>{{cite news|first=Will |last=Worley |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/media/uks-first-ever-pop-up-newspaper-the-new-european-launched-response-brexit-a7117691.html |title=UK's first ever 'pop up newspaper' to be launched in response to Brexit |newspaper=The Independent |publisher=Independent Print Limited |date=3 July 2016 |accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Roy |last=Greenslade |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/greenslade/2016/jul/04/archant-launches-pop-up-paper-to-serve-people-who-voted-remain |title=Archant launches pop-up paper to serve people who voted remain |newspaper=The Guardian |date=4 July 2016 |accessdate=16 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Opara |first=Amaka |url=http://www.pressgazette.co.uk/editor-of-pop-up-newspaper-for-the-48-the-new-european-it-has-a-future/ |title=Editor of 'pop-up newspaper for the 48%' The New European hopeful it has a future |newspaper=Press Gazette |publisher=Progressive Media International |date=18 July 2016 |accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref>

===Proposed British Independence Day national holiday===
Some [[Brexit]] supporters such as [[David Davies (Welsh politician)|David Davies]], [[Steve Double]], [[William Wragg]] and Sir [[David Amess]] called for the Brexit referendum result on 23 June 2016 to be recognised as British Independence Day and be made a [[National Day|public holiday]] in the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/conservative-right-wingers-produce-wish-13582590 |title=Conservative right-wingers produce a wish-list of policies to transform Britain |work=[[Birmingham Mail]] |date=6 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2016-06-24/farage-let-june-23-be-the-uks-independence-day/ |title=UK votes to leave the EU in historic referendum |publisher=[[ITV plc|ITV]] |date=24 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-eu-referendum-36613295 |title=EU Referendum: Farage declares 'independence day' |publisher=BBC |date=24 June 2016}}</ref> The concept was widely used in social media, with the [[BBC]] naming it as one of "Five social media trends after Brexit vote".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-trending-36625800 |title=Five social media trends after Brexit vote |publisher=BBC |date=24 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-36619223 |title=Brexit: 'Surge' in searches on Irish passports, says Google |publisher=BBC |date=24 June 2016}}</ref> With support from Conservative MP [[Nigel Evans]],<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/14838634.Who_fancies_a_Brexit_bank_holiday__One_East_Lancashire_MP_does___/ |title=Who fancies a Brexit bank holiday? One East Lancashire MP does... |publisher=[[The Press (York)]] |date=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/10/25/tory-mp-calls-for-independence-day-brexit-bank-holiday/ |title=Tory MP calls for 'Independence Day' Brexit bank holiday |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=25 October 2016}}</ref> an [[online petition]] on the [[UK Parliament]] government website calling for the date to be "designated as Independence Day, and celebrated annually" reached sufficient signatures to trigger a government response, which stated there were "no current plans to create another public holiday".<ref name="UK Parliament: Parliament debated this topic">{{cite news |title=Petition No.: 123324 - The 23 June should be designated as Independence Day, and celebrated annually |publisher=[[UK Parliament]] |date=23 June 2016}}</ref><ref name="BBC: Petitions debated on Monday">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-parliaments-37685894 |title=What happens when a petition gets debated in Parliament? |publisher=BBC |date=18 October 2016}}</ref><ref name="Yahoo: Speaking in a Westminster Hall debate">{{cite news |url=https://uk.news.yahoo.com/turns-no-current-plans-british-220927869.html |title='No current plans' for a British independence day on June 23 |publisher=[[Yahoo! News]] |date=17 October 2016 |access-date=1 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161230090733/https://uk.news.yahoo.com/turns-no-current-plans-british-220927869.html |archive-date=30 December 2016 |dead-url=yes |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

On 5 September 2017, a number of Conservative MPs backed MP [[Peter Bone]]'s June Bank Holiday (Creation) Bill in the House of Commons, for the Brexit referendum date to be a UK-wide public holiday.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://services.parliament.uk/bills/2017-19/junebankholidaycreation.html |title=June Bank Holiday (Creation) Bill 2017-19 |publisher=[[UK Parliament]] |date=5 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/conservative-right-wingers-produce-wish-13582590 |title=Conservative right-wingers produce a wish-list of policies to transform Britain |work=[[Birmingham Mail]] |date=6 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/brexit-could-become-bank-holiday-13586351 |title=Brexit could become a BANK HOLIDAY in the UK - and here's why |work=[[Coventry Telegraph]] |date=8 September 2017}}</ref> The bill proposes that "June 23 or the subsequent weekday when June 23 falls at a weekend" should serve as a national holiday.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.birminghampost.co.uk/news/regional-affairs/mps-want-brexit-bank-holiday-13577103 |title=This is why there may be another bank holiday |work=[[Birmingham Post]] |date=8 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/news/northern-ireland/brexit-bank-holiday-among-scores-of-measures-proposed-by-mps-36102798.html |title=Brexit bank holiday among scores of measures proposed by MPs |work=[[Belfast Telegraph]] |date=5 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.westmonster.com/brexit-mp-pushes-for-june-23rd-to-become-brexit-bank-holiday/ |title=Tory MP: June 23rd should be Brexit Bank Holiday |publisher=[[Westmonster]] |date=7 September 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thecanary.co/uk/2017/09/07/group-tory-mps-trying-push-law-make-everyone-pay-nhs-treatment/ |title=A group of Tory MPs are trying to push through a law to make everyone pay for NHS treatment |publisher=[[The Canary (political blog)]] |date=7 September 2017}}</ref>

==Official investigations into campaigns==

On 9 May 2016, Leave.EU was fined £50,000 by the UK [[Information Commissioner's Office]] 'for failing to follow the rules about sending marketing messages': they sent people text messages without having first gained their permission to do so.<ref>'[https://ico.org.uk/media/action-weve-taken/mpns/1624135/mpn-better-for-the-country-20160509.pdf DATA PROTECTION ACT 1998 SUPERVISORY POWERS OF THE INFORMATION COMMISSIONER MONETARY PENALTY NOTICE] (9 May 2016).</ref><ref>'[https://ico.org.uk/about-the-ico/news-and-events/news-and-blogs/2016/05/eu-campaign-firm-fined-for-sending-spam-texts/ EU campaign firm fined for sending spam texts]' (11 May 2016).</ref>

On 4 March 2017, the Information Commissioner's Office also reported that it was 'conducting a wide assessment of the data-protection risks arising from the use of data analytics, including for political purposes' in relation to the Brexit campaign. It was specified that among the organisations to be investigated was [[Cambridge Analytica]] and its relationship with the Leave.EU campaign. The findings are expected to be published sometime in 2017.<ref>Jamie Doward, Carole Cadwalladr and Alice Gibbs, '[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/mar/04/cambridge-analytics-data-brexit-trump Watchdog to launch inquiry into misuse of data in politics]', ''The Observer'' (4 March 2017).</ref><ref name="theguardian.com">Carole Cadwalladr, '[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/may/07/the-great-british-brexit-robbery-hijacked-democracy The great British Brexit robbery: how our democracy was hijacked]', ''The Observer'' (Sunday 7 May 2017).</ref>

On 21 April 2017, the [[Electoral Commission (United Kingdom)|Electoral Commission]] announced that it was investigating 'whether one or more donations – including of services – accepted by Leave.EU was impermissible; and whether Leave.EU’s spending return was complete', because 'there were reasonable grounds to suspect that potential offences under the law may have occurred'.<ref>[http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/i-am-a/journalist/electoral-commission-media-centre/news-releases-referendums/electoral-commission-statement-on-investigation-into-leave.eu Electoral Commission statement on investigation into Leave.EU] (21 April 2017).</ref><ref name="theguardian.com"/>

=== Accusations of foreign interference===
In the run up to the Brexit referendum, Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] suggested that Russia "might be happy" with a positive Brexit vote, while the Remain campaign accused the [[Kremlin]] of secretly backing a positive Brexit vote.<ref>S Rosenberg, ‘EU referendum: What does Russia gain from Brexit?’ (26 June 2016) [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-36629146 BBC News]</ref> In December 2016, [[Ben Bradshaw MP]] claimed in Parliament that it was "highly probable" that Russia had interfered in the Brexit referendum campaign.<ref>''Highly probable' that Russia interfered in Brexit referendum, Labour MP says' (13 December 2016) [https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/russian-interference-brexit-highly-probable-referendum-hacking-putin-a7472706.html Independent]</ref> In February 2017, Bradshaw called on the British intelligence service, [[Government Communications Headquarters]], currently under [[Boris Johnson]] as Foreign Secretary, to reveal the information it had on Russian interference.<ref>J Kanter and A Bienkov, 'Labour MPs think the government is hiding info about Russia interfering with Brexit' (23 February 2016) [http://uk.businessinsider.com/labour-mp-ben-bradshaw-suspicious-russian-interference-brexit-2017-2?op=1 Business Insider]</ref>

In April 2017, the [[House of Commons]] Public Administration and Constitutional Affairs Committee issued a report stating that Russian and foreign interference in the referendum was probable, including the shut down of the government voter registration website immediately before the vote.<ref>{{cite news |author=Rajeev Syal |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2017/apr/12/foreign-states-may-have-interfered-in-brexit-vote-report-says |title=Brexit: foreign states may have interfered in vote, report says |work=The Guardian |date=12 April 2017 |accessdate=13 September 2018}}</ref> In May 2017, it was reported by the ''[[Irish Times]]'' that £425,622 had potentially been donated by sources in [[Saudi Arabia]] to the "vote leave" supporting [[Democratic Unionist Party]] for spending during the referendum.<ref>F O’Toole, ‘What connects Brexit, the DUP, dark money and a Saudi prince?’ (16 May 2017) ''Irish Times''</ref>

