{{EngvarB|date=September 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}} {{more references|date=June 2014}}
[[File:Posts in Warneford Meadow 030207.JPG|thumb|upright|Two wooden posts in Warneford Meadow.]] '''Warneford Meadow''' is an area of {{convert|20|acre|ha}} of natural [[grassland]] immediately south-east of the [[Warneford Hospital]], in [[Headington]], east [[Oxford]], England. The Warneford Meadow is a wild space within urban Oxford. The area has been used by local residents as a [[public space]] for [[recreation]] for over 50 years.<ref name="Town Green">{{cite web| url=http://www.24dash.com/news/environment/2006-12-21-Warneford-Meadow-to-become-Town-Green | title=Warneford Meadow to become Town Green? | date=21 December 2006 | publisher=24dash.com | accessdate=7 June 2014 }}</ref>
==History== Warneford Meadow was purchased in 1918 by the [[Warneford Hospital]], a [[psychiatric hospital]], following the sale of the adjacent Southfield Farm.<ref>[http://www.headington.org.uk/history/listed_buildings/warneford.htm Headington News website describing the history of Warneford Hospital].</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.theoxfordtimes.net/display.var.1093753.0.nhs_dilutes_its_student_village_plan.php |title=NHS dilutes its 'student village' plan |work=Oxford Times|date=29 December 2006 |accessdate=30 March 2010}}</ref> The purchase was funded by public subscription, with the aim of providing natural green space for the psychological benefit of patients and the local community. [[Archaeology trench|Archaeological trenching]] performed in 2006 suggested a [[Ancient Rome|Roman]] or [[Prehistoric Britain|pre-Roman settlement]], or area of [[pottery]] production, in the area of the present meadow.<ref>[http://www.oxford.gov.uk/files/meetingdocs/60257/item4-pt1.pdf An Oxford City council planning document (pdf) discussing the archeological findings].</ref>
==Geography== [[File:Warneford meadow Tom Capon 1.jpg|thumb|Warneford Meadow in summer.]] Access to the Meadow is gained from either a lane off Hill Top Road, beside the Southfield Park Golf Club, or Roosevelt Drive opposite the 'Little Oxford' housing development (beside the Headington Care Home). The Meadow slopes gradually down from the Hill Top Road end, towards the Boundary Brook, which runs between the Meadow and the [[Churchill Hospital]] to the East. Several public paths run across the Meadow. South of the Meadow is the Southfield Park Golf Club and the Meadow is bounded to the west by homes on Hill Top Road. Warneford Meadow also includes an orchard, on the northern border of the Meadow with the [[Warneford Hospital]].
==Biodiversity== The Meadow contains species of [[butterfly]], [[invertebrates]], and birds including [[skylark]]s and [[kingfishers]]. The Meadow forms part of the 'green corridor' which links South Park to the [[Thames]] via Boundary Brook.{{Citation needed|date=April 2010}} The Meadow's border hedges include [[Blackberry|backberries]]. The Warneford Orchard on the northern edge of the Meadow is over 50 years old and has varieties of apple including the Russian ''Emperor Alexander''.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}} [[Owls]], [[bat]]s, and [[badgers]] are also found in the orchard.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}
==Development== [[File:Sunrise over Warneford Meadow 030207.JPG|thumb|Sunrise over the Warneford Meadow in winter.]] Development of the Meadow is permitted under the Oxford Local Plan 2001–2016.<ref>[http://www.oxford.gov.uk/PageRender/decP/Oxford_Local_Plan_occw.htm Oxford Local Plan 2001–2016]</ref> The [[Oxfordshire & Buckinghamshire Mental Health Partnership NHS Trust]] (OBMH) submitted two outline planning applications in July 2006, regarding the Meadow. The primary reason for the development, stated by the OBMH management, was the desire to generate capital for the Trust, in order to upgrade patient facilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.obmh.nhs.uk/?p=1858 |title=Update on planning applications |work=Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Mental Health NHS Foundation Trust |date=20 November 2007 |accessdate=30 March 2010}}</ref> In answer to a parliamentary question about the assets of the United Kingdom's [[National Health Service|NHS]] as a whole [[Liam Byrne]], the [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]], revealed that the 'surplus' land at the Warneford Hospital was worth £30,900,000.<ref>[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2006-01-12c.36306.h Theyworkforyou.com] – Liam Byrne MP clarifying the most valuable assets owned by the Department of Health.</ref><ref>[http://www.headington.org.uk/news/items/2006/warneford_meadow.htm Headington News website with details of the planning proposals submitted to Oxford County Council], 2006.</ref>
The plans for development met with substantial opposition from local residents, led by nearby Residents Associations and the action group 'Friends of Warneford Meadow'.{{citation needed|date=October 2012}}
An application to have the land registered as a [[Village green|Town or Village Green]] (under section 22 of the [[Commons Registration Act 1965]], amended by section 98 of the [[Countryside and Rights of Way Act 2000]]).<ref>[http://www.defra.gov.uk/wildlife-countryside/issues/common/town-villagegreens/index.htm UK government/DEFRA website outlining legislation on Town or Village greens]</ref> was launched in December 2006.<ref name="Town Green"/> The application was successful, and Warneford Meadow was designated as a Town Green in April 2009.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/oxfordshire/7986428.stm Meadow Protected From Developers], [[BBC News]], 6 April 2009. Retrieved 23 August 2009.</ref> Oxfordshire and Buckinghamshire Mental Health NHS Foundation Trust challenged the decision in the High Court;<ref>[http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/search/4424678.NHS_to_appeal_on_Oxford_meadow_being_a__town_green_/ NHS to appeal on Oxford meadow being a "town green"], ''[[Oxford Mail]]'', 8 June 2009. Retrieved 23 August 2009.</ref> the action commenced in February 2010. In March 2010 the High Court upheld the original decision to register the meadow as a Town Green.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/headlines/5081069.Meadow_campaigners_celebrate_a_new_dawn/ |title=Meadow campaigners celebrate a new dawn |date=24 March 2010 |work=Oxford Mail | accessdate=25 March 2010}}</ref>
